 \n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|-\n| align=center|{{sort|47|47}} \n| align=center|{{sort|38|38}} \n| [[Martin H. Kennelly]] \n| 1947\n| 1955\n| align=center| 2\n| align=center| 8\n| bgcolor={{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}| \n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|-\n| align=center|{{sort|48|48}} \n| align=center|{{sort|39|39}} \n| [[Richard J. Daley]] \u2020\n| 1955\n| 1976\n| align=center| 5 {{sort|.25|{{frac|3|8}}}}\n| align=center| 21 \n| bgcolor={{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}| \n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|-\n| align=center|{{sort|49|49}} \n| align=center|{{sort|40|40}} \n| [[Michael A. Bilandic]] \n| 1976\n| 1979\n| align=center|  {{sort|.625|{{frac|5|8}}}}\n| align=center| 2 {{sort|.33|{{frac|1|3}}}}\n| bgcolor={{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}| \n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|-\n| align=center|{{sort|50|50}} \n| align=center|{{sort|41|41}} \n| [[Jane Byrne]] \n| 1979\n| 1983\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 4\n| bgcolor={{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}| \n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|-\n| align=center|{{sort|51|51}} \n| align=center|{{sort|42|42}} \n| [[Harold Washington]] \u2020\n| 1983\n| 1987\n| align=center| 1 {{sort|.125|{{frac|1|8}}}}\n| align=center| 4 {{sort|.58|{{frac|7|12}}}}\n| bgcolor={{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}| \n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|-\n| align=center|{{sort|52|52}} \n| align=center|{{sort|43|43}} \n| [[David Orr]]<br>(acting mayor)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/1443.html|title=Chicago Mayors, 1837-2007|author=|date=|website=www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org|accessdate=19 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707145531/http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/1443.html|archive-date=7 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| 1987\n| 1987\n| align=center| \n|\n| bgcolor={{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}| \n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|-\n| align=center|{{sort|53|53}} \n| align=center|{{sort|44|44}} \n| [[Eugene Sawyer]] \n| 1987\n| 1989\n| align=center| {{sort|.354|{{frac|17|48}}}}\n| align=center| 1 {{sort|.5|{{frac|1|2}}}}\n| bgcolor={{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}| \n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|-\n| align=center|{{sort|54|54}} \n| align=center|{{sort|45|45}} \n| [[Richard M. Daley]] \n| 1989\n| 2011\n| align=center| 5 {{sort|.5|{{frac|1|2}}}}\n| align=center| 22\n| bgcolor={{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}| \n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n| align=center|{{sort|55|55}} \n| align=center|{{sort|46|46}} \n| [[Rahm Emanuel]] \n| 2011\n| 2019\n| align=center| 2\n| align=center| 8\n| bgcolor={{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}| \n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n| align=center|{{sort|56|56}} \n| align=center|{{sort|47|47}} \n| [[Lori Lightfoot]]\n| 2019\n| \n| align=center| \n| align=center| \n| bgcolor={{Democratic Party (United States)/meta/color}}| \n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]<sup>1</sup>\n|}\n\n<sup>\u2020</sup> Deceased/murdered in office.<br>\n<sup>1</sup> Since 1999, mayoral elections have officially been nonpartisan.  A 1995 Illinois law stipulated that \"candidates for mayor . . . no longer would run under party labels in Chicago.\"  However, Richard M. Daley, Rahm Emanuel and Lori Lightfoot are known to be Democrats.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gov. Edgar To End City Partisan Votes|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-07-07/news/9507070087_1_nonpartisan-election-election-commissioners-first-black-mayor|publisher=Chicago Tribune|first=Thomas|last=Hardy|date=July 7, 1995|access-date=September 25, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007120504/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-07-07/news/9507070087_1_nonpartisan-election-election-commissioners-first-black-mayor|archive-date=October 7, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Living mayors==\nAs of 2018, four mayors of Chicago are still living, the oldest of whom is [[Richard M. Daley]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Chicago Mayors|url=http://www.chipublib.org/chicago-mayors/|website=Chicago Public Library|accessdate=8 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023145348/http://www.chipublib.org/chicago-mayors/|archive-date=23 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The most recent former mayor to die was [[Jane Margaret Byrne|Jane Byrne]] (1979&ndash;1983), on November 14, 2014. The most recently serving mayor to have died, however, was [[Eugene Sawyer]] (1987&ndash;1989), on January 19, 2008.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chipublib.org/mayor-eugene-sawyer-biography/|title=Mayor Eugene Sawyer Biography|access-date=2016-10-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503015224/http://www.chipublib.org/mayor-eugene-sawyer-biography/|archive-date=2016-05-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Name!!Mayoral term!!Date of birth\n|- {{Party shading/Democratic}}<!-- party shading is not working -->|-\n| [[David Orr]]\n|November 1987 \u2013 December 1987\n|{{birth date and age|1944|10|4}}\n|- {{Party shading/Democratic}}<!-- party shading is not working -->|-\n| [[Richard M. Daley]]\n|1989\u20132011\n|{{birth date and age|1942|4|24}}\n|- {{Party shading/Democratic}}<!-- party shading is not working -->\n|[[Rahm Emanuel]]\n|2011\u20132019\n|{{birth date and age|1959|11|29}}\n|- {{Party shading/Democratic}}<!-- party shading is not working -->\n|[[Lori Lightfoot]]\n|2019&ndash;present\n|{{birth date and age|1962|8|4}}\n|}\n\n==Vice Mayor==\nIn accordance with Illinois law, the city council elects a vice mayor who serves as interim mayor in the event of a vacancy in the office of the mayor or the inability of the mayor to serve due to illness or injury, until the city council elects one of its members [[acting (law)|acting]] mayor or until the mayoral term expires. As of May 2019, the current vice mayor is [[Tom Tunney]].<ref name=tunneyvice1/>\n\nThe position was created by state law after the power struggle that took place of [[Richard J. Daley]]'s [[death in office]].<ref name=king1976/><ref>{{cite web |title=Another City Council Stealth Budget \u2013 ChicagoTalks |url=http://www.chicagotalks.org/?p=6353 |publisher=Chicago Talks |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=65 ILCS 20/21-5.1 |url=http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/ilcs/documents/006500200K21-5.1.htm |website=www.ilga.gov |publisher=Illinois General Assembly |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe position is considered to be largely ceremonial.<ref name=spielman/><ref name=dumke/>\n\nIf neither the mayor nor pro tempore can preside over a City Council meeting, then the vice mayor presides.<ref name=krebs/>\n\nThe inaugural holder of this office was [[Casimir Laskowski]].<ref>{{cite web |title=CASIMIR LASKOWSKI, 84 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2003-08-18-0308180077-story.html |website=chicagotribune.com |publisher=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=18 August 2013}}</ref> Other past holders of this office have included [[Terry Gabinski]] (1988-1998),<ref name=dold1>{{cite web |last1=Dold |first1=R. Bruce |title=COUNCIL REPLACES ORR AS VICE MAYOR |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1988-05-26-8801020651-story.html |website=chicagotribune.com |publisher=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=26 May 1988}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Tribune |first1=Chicago |title=GABINSKI'S TOP AIDE LIKELY TO SUCCEED HIM |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1998-05-20-9805200148-story.html |website=chicagotribune.com |publisher=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=5 May 1988}}</ref> [[Richard Mell]](1979-1987),<ref>{{cite web |title=Chicago City Council: Richard Mell |url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/politics/chicago-city-council-profile-richard-f-mell/1897935/ |website=NBC Chicago |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> [[David Orr]] (1987-1988),<ref name=\"wilsonfrost\"/><ref name=dold1/><ref name=dicksimpson>{{cite book |last1=Simpson |first1=Dick |title=Rogues, Rebels, And Rubber Stamps: The Politics Of The Chicago City Council, 1863 To The Present |date=2018 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-429-97719-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jQlQDwAAQBAJ |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Brendan Reilly (politician)|Brendan Reilly]] (2015\u20132019)<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sullivan |first1=Emmet |title=What Would Actually Happen if Rahm Resigns |url=https://www.chicagomag.com/city-life/December-2015/mayoral-succession/ |website=ChicagoMag.org |publisher=Chicago Magazine |accessdate=March 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/politics/ct-met-chicago-city-council-lori-lightfoot-reorganization-20190528-story.html|title=Chicago Mayor Lori Lightfoot aces first test of her power: City Council overhaul approved|last=Pratt|first=John Byrne, Juan Perez Jr , Gregory|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> [[Bernard Stone]] (1998-2011),<ref name=dicksimpson/><ref>{{cite web |title=Chicago's Vice Mayor |url=http://chicagotonight.wttw.com/2010/04/13/chicagos-vice-mayor |work=[[Chicago Tonight]]|publisher=[[WTTW]]  |date=April 10, 2010 |accessdate=July 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Geiger |first1=Kim |last2=Washburn |first2=Gay |title=Former Chicago Alderman Bernie Stone dead at 87 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/breaking/chi-bernie-stone-dead-20141222-story.html |website=chicagotribune.com |publisher=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=22 December 2014}}</ref> [[Ray Suarez (politician)|Ray Suarez]] (2011\u20132015),<ref name=spielman>{{cite web |last1=Spielman |first1=Fran |title=City Council shuffle rewards Emanuel allies |url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/7/71/622429/city-council-sign-reorganization-rewards-emanuel-allies |publisher=Chicago Sun-Times |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151207033030/https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/7/71/622429/city-council-sign-reorganization-rewards-emanuel-allies |archivedate=7 December 2012 |date=20 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=dumke>{{cite web |last1=Dumke |first1=Mick |title=The first meeting of the new mayor and City Council is nothing if not efficient |url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2011/05/18/the-first-meeting-of-the-new-mayor-and-city-council-is-nothing-if-not-efficient |website=Chicago Reader |accessdate=1 March 2020 |language=en |date=18 May 2011}}</ref> and [[Edward Vrdolyak]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fujinaga |first1=Yasumasa |title=Black Power at the Polls: The Harold Washington Campaign of 1983 and the Demise of the Democratic Machine in Chicago |journal=The Japanese Journal of American Studies |issue=25 |url=http://www.jaas.gr.jp/jjas/PDF/2014/05_Fujinaga.pdf |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Chicago}}\n* [[Law and government of Chicago]]\n* [[Timeline of Chicago history]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.chipublib.org/cplbooksmovies/cplarchive/mayors/mayorlist.php |title=A Chronology of Chicago's Mayors |publisher=[[Chicago Public Library]] |accessdate=2010-05-26}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Mayors of Chicago}}\n* [http://www.cityofchicago.org/city/en/depts/mayor.html Mayor's official webpage]\n\n{{-}}\n{{Mayors of Chicago}}\n{{Chicago municipal government officials}}\n{{Chicago}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mayor Of Chicago}}\n[[Category:1837 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Government of Chicago]]\n[[Category:Lists of mayors of places in Illinois|Chicago]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Chicago| ]]\n[[Category:People from Chicago|*]]\n", "name_user": "SecretName101", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo\u2192\u200eVice Mayor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mayor_of_Chicago"}
{"title_page": "Adam Sandler", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor, comedian, screenwriter, and producer}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name    = Adam Sandler\n| image   = Adam Sandler 2011 (Cropped).jpg\n| caption = Sandler receiving his star on the<br/> [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in February 2011\n| birth_name = Adam Richard Sandler\n| alias   = <!--This field is for official stage names, ''not'' for nicknames.-->\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|9|9}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], New York, U.S.\n| years_active = 1987\u2013present<ref>{{cite book|author1=Geoffrey M. Horn|title=Adam Sandler|date=2006|publisher=Gareth Stevens|isbn=0836842340|page=[https://archive.org/details/adamsandler0000horn/page/17 17]|url=https://archive.org/details/adamsandler0000horn|url-access=registration|quote=adam sandler 1987 cosby show.|accessdate=April 22, 2018}}</ref>\n| occupation = {{Flat list|\n*Actor\n*comedian\n*screenwriter\n*film producer\n*singer-songwriter}}\n| alma_mater = [[New York University]]\n| party =\n| spouse   = {{marriage|Jacqueline Titone|2003}}\n| children = 2\n| signature =\n| module = {{Infobox comedian|embed=yes\n| medium =  [[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]], [[film]], [[television]]\n| genre =\n| website  = {{url|adamsandler.com}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Adam Richard Sandler''' (born September 9, 1966) is an American actor, comedian, screenwriter, film producer, and singer-songwriter. After becoming a ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' cast member, he went on to star in many Hollywood feature films, which have combined grossed over $2 billion at the box office.<ref>{{cite web |title=People Index |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/?view=Actor&sort=sumgross&p=.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326160457/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/?view=Actor&sort=sumgross&p=.htm |archive-date=26 March 2018 |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Adam Sandler |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/person/126870401-Adam-Sandler#tab=summary |publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nSandler is best known for his comedic roles including ''[[Billy Madison]]'' (1995), ''[[Happy Gilmore]]'' (1996), ''[[The Waterboy]]'' (1998), ''[[The Wedding Singer]]'' (1998), ''[[Big Daddy (1999 film)|Big Daddy]]'' (1999), ''[[Mr. Deeds]]'' (2002), ''[[50 First Dates]]'' (2004), ''[[The Longest Yard (2005 film)|The Longest Yard]]'' (2005), ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]'' (2006), ''[[Grown Ups (film)|Grown Ups]]'' (2010), ''[[Just Go with It]]'' (2011), ''[[Grown Ups 2]]'' (2013), ''[[Blended (film)|Blended]]'' (2014), ''[[Murder Mystery (film)|Murder Mystery]]'' (2019). He also voices [[Count Dracula|Dracula]] in the [[Hotel Transylvania (franchise)|''Hotel Transylvania'' franchise]] (2012\u2013present).\n\nSome of his films, such as the widely panned ''[[Jack and Jill (2011 film)|Jack and Jill]]'', have been heavily criticized, culminating in a shared second place in the number of [[Raspberry Awards]] (three) and Raspberry Award nominations (11), in both cases second only to [[Sylvester Stallone]].\n\nSandler ventured into dramatic territory with his roles in ''[[Punch-Drunk Love]]'' (2002), ''[[Spanglish (film)|Spanglish]]'' (2004), ''[[Reign Over Me]]'' (2007), ''[[Funny People]]'' (2009), ''[[The Meyerowitz Stories|The Meyerowitz Stories (New and Selected)]]'' (2017), and ''[[Uncut Gems]]'' (2019), all of which earned him critical praise.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cea|first=Max|url=https://www.salon.com/2017/10/12/noah-baumbach-performs-a-miracle-adam-sandler-doesnt-suck-in-the-meyerowitz-stories/|title=Noah Baumbach performs a miracle: Adam Sandler doesn't suck in 'The Meyerowitz Stories' |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=October 12, 2017|accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nSandler was born in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], on September 9, 1966,<ref name=filmref /><ref name=biography.com>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/adam-sandler-9542505|title=Adam Sandler: Film Actor, Singer, Songwriter, Comedian, Screenwriter (1966\u2013)|website=[[Biography.com]]|publisher=[[A&E Networks]]| accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Monitor|newspaper=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=September 13, 2013|issue=1276|pages=28}}</ref> to Judith \"Judy\" (n\u00e9e Levine), a nursery school teacher, and Stanley Sandler, an electrical engineer.<ref name=\"filmref\">{{cite web| url = http://www.filmreference.com/film/70/Adam-Sandler.html |title=Adam Sandler Biography (1966?-)|publisher= FilmReference.com|accessdate=December 24, 2014 | quote=Full name, Adam Richard Sandler; born September 9, 1966 (some sources cite 1964)...}}</ref> His family is [[Jews|Jewish]] and descends from Russian Jewish immigrants on both sides.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jewishjournal.com/opinion/rob_eshman/180474/|title=Adam Sandler: \"I'm very pro-Israel\"|last=Eshman|first=Rob|date=December 15, 2015|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|Jewish Journal]]|accessdate=May 20, 2018|quote=\"I'm proud of being a Jew and that's what I am,\" Sandler said.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/3709985/Adam-Sandler-this-ones-for-the-kids.html|title=Adam Sandler: this one's for the kids|last=Hiscock|first=John|date=December 11, 2008|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=July 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/196117/adam-sandler-and-howard-stern-talk-jewish-shop|title= Adam Sandler and Howard Stern Talk Jewish Shop |first=Jonathan |last=Zalman |work=[[Tablet (magazine)|Tablet Magazine]]|date= December 22, 2015|accessdate= April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/i-didnt-get-into-movies-to-please-the-critics-adam-sandler-interview-8742294.html|title= 'I didn't get into movies to please the critics': Adam Sandler interview |work=[[The Independent]]|first=Emma |last=Jones |date= August 2, 2013|accessdate= April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=\u0413\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0413\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0430 |url=http://www.golos-ameriki.ru/content/just-go-with-it-2011-03-21-118361894/224464.html |title=\u041f\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u043a \u0410\u0434\u0430\u043c\u0430 \u0421\u044d\u043d\u0434\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0430 \u0438 \u0414\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0444\u0435\u0440 \u042d\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043d |website=Golos-ameriki.ru |date=March 21, 2011 |accessdate=June 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bh.org.il/blog-items/stars-of-david-10-jewish-hollywood-icons/|title=Let There Be Laughter \u2013 Jewish Humor Around the World|last=|first=|date=|website=Beit Hatfutsot|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> His [[patrilineal]] great-grandfather, Joseph Jacob Sandler, was born in  [[Pag\u0117giai Municipality]], [[Taurag\u0117 County]], [[Lithuania]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.geni.com/people/Joseph-Sandler/6000000029081386829?through=6000000038200170005 | title=Joseph Jacob Sandler (1878 - 1952) | publisher=[[Geni.com]] | date=January 20, 2019 | accessdate=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Sandler grew up in [[Manchester, New Hampshire]], after moving there at the age of six.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unionleader.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/99999999/NEWHAMPSHIRE09/110429372/-1/newhampshire09|title=Adam Sandler|work=UnionLeader.com}}</ref> He attended [[Manchester Central High School]]. As a teen, Sandler was in [[BBYO]], a Jewish youth group. Sandler graduated from [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]] in 1988.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.nyu.edu/alumni.magazine/issue10/10_culture_snl.html | title= Live From New York, It's... | publisher=[[New York University]] | work=NYU Alumni Magazine | date= Spring 2008 | accessdate=June 30, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100530061407/http://www.nyu.edu/alumni.magazine/issue10/10_culture_snl.html| archivedate= May 30, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Acting career ===\n[[File:Adamsandler(cannesPhotocall).jpg|thumb|Sandler at 2002 [[Cannes Film Festival]]]]\nEarly in his career, in 1987, Sandler played [[Theo Huxtable]]'s friend, Smitty, in ''[[The Cosby Show]]'' and the Stud Boy or Trivia Delinquent in the [[Game show|MTV game show]] ''[[Remote Control (game show)|Remote Control]]''. After his film debut ''[[Going Overboard]]'' in 1989, Sandler performed in comedy clubs, having first taken the stage at his brother's urging when he was 17. He was discovered by comedian [[Dennis Miller]], who caught Sandler's act in Los Angeles and recommended him to ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' producer [[Lorne Michaels]]. Sandler was hired as a writer for ''SNL'' in 1990 and became a featured player the following year, making a name for himself by performing amusing original songs on the show, including \"[[The Thanksgiving Song]]\" and \"[[The Chanukah Song]]\".<ref name=biography.com/> Sandler told [[Conan O'Brien]] on ''[[The Tonight Show with Conan O'Brien|The Tonight Show]]'' that [[NBC]] fired him and [[Chris Farley]] from the show in 1995, and played this up in his return to the show as a host in 2019.<ref name=\"Sandler fired\">{{cite news| url = http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/2010/01/21/2010-01-21_youre_not_alone_conan_obrien_adam_sandler_says_nbc_fired_him_and_chris_farley_fr.html | title= You're not alone, Conan O'Brien: Adam Sandler says NBC fired him and Chris Farley from 'SNL'| first= Joe |last=Dziemianowicz| work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] | location=New York City |date= January 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Adam Sandler's \"I Was Fired\" Monologue - SNL |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eghK5yMpNuc |publisher=SNL}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Adam Sandler appeared in the film ''[[Coneheads (film)|Coneheads]]'' with Chris Farley, [[David Spade]], [[Dan Aykroyd]], [[Phil Hartman]], and [[Jane Curtin]]. In 1994, he co-starred in ''[[Airheads]]'' with [[Brendan Fraser]] and [[Steve Buscemi]]. He starred in ''[[Billy Madison]]'' (1995) playing a grown man repeating grades 1\u201312 to earn back his father's respect and the right to inherit his father's multimillion-dollar hotel empire. The film was successful at the box office despite negative reviews. He followed this film with ''[[Bulletproof (1996 film)|Bulletproof]]'' (1996), and the financially successful comedies ''Happy Gilmore'' (1996) and ''The Wedding Singer'' (1998). He was initially cast in the bachelor party\u2013themed comedy/thriller ''[[Very Bad Things]]'' (1998) but had to back out due to his involvement in ''[[The Waterboy]]'' (1998), one of his first hits.\n\nAlthough his earliest films did not receive favorable critical attention, he started to receive more positive reviews, beginning with ''Punch-Drunk Love'' in 2002. [[Roger Ebert]]'s review of ''Punch-Drunk Love'' concluded that Sandler had been wasted in earlier films with poorly written scripts and characters with no development.<ref>Ebert, Roger. [http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20021018/REVIEWS/210180308/1023 \"Punch-Drunk Love.\"] ''Chicago Sun-Times''. October 18, 2002.</ref> Sandler has moved outside the genre of slapstick comedy to take on more serious roles, such as the aforementioned ''[[Punch-Drunk Love]]'', for which he was nominated for a [[Golden Globe]], and [[Mike Binder]]'s ''[[Reign Over Me]]'' (2007), a drama about a man who loses his entire family during the [[September 11 attacks]], and then struggles to rekindle a friendship with his old college roommate ([[Don Cheadle]]).\n\nHe starred alongside friend [[Kevin James]] in the film ''[[I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry]]'' (2007), and headlined ''[[You Don't Mess with the Zohan]]'' (2008). The latter film was written by Sandler, [[Judd Apatow]], and [[Robert Smigel]], and directed by [[Dennis Dugan]].\n\n[[File:Adam Sandler 6818.jpg|thumb|left|Sandler in [[Berlin]] in 2009]]\nSandler starred along with [[Keri Russell]] and English comedian [[Russell Brand]] in [[Adam Shankman]]'s fantasy film ''[[Bedtime Stories (film)|Bedtime Stories]]'' (2008), as a stressed hotel maintenance worker whose bedtime stories he reads to his niece and nephew begin to come true. It marked as Sandler's first family film and first film under the [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney]] banner.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=19719 |title=Adam Sandler's Bedtime Stories Come True| website=ComingSoon.net | date= April 4, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Sandler starred in Judd Apatow's third directorial feature ''[[Funny People]]''. The film was released on July 31, 2009.<ref>{{cite news | author=Michael Fleming | title = Trio joins Judd Apatow film |work=Variety | date = June 11, 2008 | url = https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117987337.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | accessdate=June 13, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080709034441/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117987337.html?categoryid=13&cs=1| archivedate=July 9, 2008| url-status= live}}</ref> Following the release of ''Funny People'', it, along with ''Punch-Drunk Love'' were cited in the June 2010 announcement that Sandler was one of 135 people (including 20 actors) invited to join the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2010/20100625.html | title= Academy Invites 135 to Membership | publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] | work=[[Press release]] | date= June 25, 2010 | location= Beverly Hills, CA | accessdate=June 29, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100630164148/http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2010/20100625.html| archivedate= June 30, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nSandler appeared in ''[[Grown Ups (film)|Grown Ups]]'', alongside Kevin James, [[Chris Rock]], [[Rob Schneider]], and David Spade. Sandler and ''Dickie Roberts'' scribe Fred Wolf wrote the script and Dennis Dugan directed the film.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117999951.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | title = Columbia pic gets Sandler and friends |work=Variety | date = February 10, 2009 | accessdate=February 12, 2009 | first=Tatiana | last=Siegel| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090213130229/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117999951.html?categoryid=13&cs=1| archivedate= February 13, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nSandler starred with [[Jennifer Aniston]] in the 2011 romantic comedy film ''[[Just Go with It]]''. Sandler also voiced a capuchin monkey in Kevin James's ''[[Zookeeper (film)|Zookeeper]]'', released on July 8, 2011. In 2012, he starred in ''[[That's My Boy (2012 film)|That's My Boy]]'', as a man who fathered a son ([[Andy Samberg]]) with his teacher in high school.\n\nSandler starred with [[Drew Barrymore]] in the [[Warner Bros.]] romantic comedy ''[[Blended (film)|Blended]]'', which was filmed in [[South Africa]], and was released on May 23, 2014.\n\nIn 2013, he guest starred in the [[Disney Channel Original Series]] ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'' as himself. He and [[Cameron Boyce]] previously worked together in ''Grown Ups'' and ''[[Grown Ups 2]]''. The episode is titled \"Punched Dumped Love\". Sandler co-starred in the drama film ''[[Men, Women & Children (film)|Men, Women & Children]]'' (2014), directed by [[Jason Reitman]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Toronto: Jason Reitman Lining Up His Next Film|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/toronto-jason-reitman-lining-up-620958|accessdate=19 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=September 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|publisher=Paramount Pictures|title=Production Begins on Jason Reitman's Men, Women & Children|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=112527|accessdate=December 19, 2013|via=ComingSoon.net|date=December 16, 2013}}</ref> He was considered for the voice of Rocket Raccoon in Marvel's ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' but [[Bradley Cooper]] was cast instead.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ifc.com/2013/01/jim-carrey-adam-sandler-guardians-of-the-galaxy| publisher=[[IFC (U.S. TV channel)|IFC]] | title= Jim Carrey and Adam Sandler Being Considered For \"Guardians of the Galaxy\"| accessdate= October 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSandler's recent comedy films, including ''Grown Ups'' and ''Grown Ups 2'', have received strongly negative reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/grown-ups-2-best-lines-584676|title='Grown Ups 2': The Best Lines from the Worst Reviews|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=July 12, 2013|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> In reviewing the latter, critic Mark Olsen of ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' remarked that Sandler had become the antithesis of [[Judd Apatow]]; he was instead \"the white [[Tyler Perry]]: smart enough to know better, savvy enough to do it anyway, lazy enough not to care.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-grown-ups-2-review-20130712-story.html|title='Review: 'Grown Ups 2' refuses to leave the sandbox|work=The Los Angeles Times|date=July 11, 2013|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Sandler released his last theatrical film ''[[Pixels (2015 film)|Pixels]]'', based on French director Patrick Jean's [[Pixels (2010 film)|2010 short film of the same name]], before transitioning into a distribution deal with [[Netflix]]. His first original film for Netflix was the Western comedy film ''[[The Ridiculous 6]]''. Despite being universally panned by critics,<ref name=\"rotten\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_ridiculous_six/ |title= The Ridiculous Six (2015) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=December 15, 2015}}</ref> on January 6, 2016, it was announced by Netflix that the film had been viewed more times in 30 days than any other movie in Netflix history.<ref>[https://variety.com/2016/film/news/adam-sandlers-ridiculous-six-is-making-history-for-netflix-1201673572 Adam Sandle'\u2019s 'Ridiculous Six' Is Making History for Netflix] ''Variety.com''.</ref> He released three additional films on Netflix between 2016 and 2018: ''[[The Do-Over]]'', ''[[Sandy Wexler]]'' and ''[[The Week Of]]''.\n\nHe returned to dramatic territory in 2017 with ''[[The Meyerowitz Stories]]'', with his performance receiving favorable notices from critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2017/10/12/noah-baumbach-performs-a-miracle-adam-sandler-doesnt-suck-in-the-meyerowitz-stories/|title=Noah Baumbach performs a miracle: Adam Sandler doesn't suck in \"The Meyerowitz Stories\"|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|date=October 12, 2017|accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2019, Sandler made his first appearance as host of SNL, ending the episode with a tribute to his friend and fellow former cast member [[Chris Farley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/snl-adam-sandler-hosts-first-time-pays-tribute-chris-farley-1207490|title='SNL': Adam Sandler Hosts For First Time, Pays Tribute to Chris Farley|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, Sandler starred in the crime thriller drama ''[[Uncut Gems]]'', directed by the [[Safdie brothers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Adam Sandler Shows Off His Acting Chops In \u2018Uncut Gems\u2019 Trailer |url=https://digg.com/video/adam-sandler-uncut-gems-trailer |publisher=Digg |accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref> The movie and Sandler's acting received acclaim and many end of year awards from critics, who noted this role as a career best for Sandler.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/uncut-gems-review-adam-sandler-safdie-brothers-cast-director-a9276151.html|title='Uncut Gems review: The best performance of Adam Sandler\u2019s career'|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/10/04/uncut-gems-review-the-best-movie-of-adam-sandlers-career/|title=\u2018Uncut Gems\u2019 review: The best movie of Adam Sandler\u2019s career|publisher=New York Post|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Happy Madison Productions ===\n[[File:Adam Sandler (cropped).jpg|thumb|Sandler at a press conference for ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]'' in 2005]]\nSandler formed his film production company, [[Happy Madison Productions]],<ref name=\"happy\">[http://www.adamsandler.com/index.php?section=happy \"Happy Madison.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051118222008/http://www.adamsandler.com/index.php?section=happy |date=November 18, 2005 }} AdamSandler.com. Accessed October 9, 2008.</ref> in 1999, first producing fellow ''SNL'' alumnus [[Rob Schneider]]'s film ''[[Deuce Bigalow: Male Gigolo]]''. The company has produced most of Sandler's subsequent films to date. The majority of the company's films have received negative reviews from critics, with three considered to be among the [[List of films considered the worst|worst ever made]]<ref>[https://www.metacritic.com/feature/adam-sandler-all-films-considered Adam Sandler: All Films Considered] Metacritic. Accessed April 21, 2015.</ref> yet most have performed well at box office.\n\nOthers who frequently appear in Sandler films include [[David Spade]], [[Kevin James]], [[Steve Buscemi]], [[Chris Rock]], [[John Turturro]], [[Peter Dante]], [[Allen Covert]], [[Jonathan Loughran]], and [[Jon Lovitz]].\n\nIn 2014, Netflix announced a four-movie deal with Adam Sandler and Happy Madison Productions.<ref>{{Cite web|title = With Four New Adam Sandler Films, Netflix Takes Aim at Theaters - NYTimes.com|url = http://mobile.nytimes.com/2014/10/02/business/media/with-four-new-adam-sandler-films-netflix-takes-aim-at-theaters.html|website = mobile.nytimes.com|accessdate = 2015-12-13}}</ref>\n\nThe company is located on the Sony/[[Columbia Pictures]] lot in [[Culver City, California]].\n\n==Public image==\nSandler has been referenced multiple times in various media, including in the TV shows ''[[The Simpsons]]'' in the episode \"[[Monty Can't Buy Me Love]]\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bbc.adactio.com/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season10/page20.shtml|title=Monty Can't Buy Me|website=[[BBC Online]]|date=September 2005|access-date=August 11, 2017}}</ref> in ''[[Family Guy]]'' in the episode \"[[Stew-Roids]]\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ign.com/articles/2009/04/27/family-guy-stew-roids-review|title=Family Guy: \"Stew-Roids\" Review|website=[[IGN]]|first=Ahsan|last=Haque|date=April 27, 2009|access-date=August 11, 2017}}</ref> and in ''[[South Park]]'' in the episode \"[[You're Getting Old]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2011/06/09/south-park-watch-the-tao-of-poo/|title=South Park Watch: The Tao of Poo|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |first=James|last=Poniewozik|date=June 9, 2011|access-date=August 11, 2017}}</ref> He was also referenced in the video game ''[[Half-Life: Opposing Force]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vgfacts.com/trivia/6729/|title=Half-Life: Opposing Force|publisher=[[Did You Know Gaming?#VGFacts|VGFacts]]|author=\"RetroRex\"|access-date=August 11, 2017|quote=There is a hidden message on the upper skybox texture in the V-22 osprey g-man sequence. It reads \"HACK HACK HACK ALL DAY LONG. HACK HACK HACK WHILE I SING THIS SONG\". This is a reference to the Adam Sandler song \"The Beating Of A High School Janitor.}}</ref> The [[HBO]] series ''[[Animals (U.S. TV series)|Animals]]'' episode \"The Trial\" features a mock court case to decide whether Sandler or [[Jim Carrey]] is a better comedian.\n\n==Personal life==\nOn <!--Sunday--> June 22, 2003, Sandler married model-actress Jacqueline Titone.<ref name=married>{{cite news|url=https://siouxcityjournal.com/entertainment/adam-sandler-marries-model-actress-jackie-titone/article_268844b3-7fc8-5d98-af1c-36ff72ea3bdd.html|title=Adam Sandler marries model-actress Jackie Titone|agency=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[Sioux City Journal]]|date=<!--Tuesday-->June 24, 2003|accessdate=March 26, 2019|archivedate=March 26, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326152430/https://siouxcityjournal.com/entertainment/adam-sandler-marries-model-actress-jackie-titone/article_268844b3-7fc8-5d98-af1c-36ff72ea3bdd.html|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Titone had [[Conversion to Judaism|converted]] to Sandler's religion, Judaism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/nydn-features/numbers-drew-adam-article-1.643235 |title=By The Numbers Drew & Adam |work=New York Daily News |date=February 17, 2004 |accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> She makes frequent appearances in her husband's films. The couple have two daughters, born in May 2006,<ref>{{cite web|last=Wihlborg |first=Ulrica|url=https://people.com/celebrity/adam-sandler-wife-have-a-baby/|title=Adam Sandler, Wife Have a Baby|work=People|date=May 7, 2006|accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> and November 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE4AB18Q20081112|title=Adam Sandler and wife have second daughter|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=November 12, 2008|accessdate=February 3, 2018}}</ref> who also make frequent appearances in his films.\n\nSandler is a registered [[Republican Party (U.S.)|Republican]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Adam Sandler\u2019s Religion and Political Views |url=https://hollowverse.com/adam-sandler/ |website=hollowverse.com |accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref> In 2007, Sandler made a $1 million donation to the [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America]] in his hometown, [[Manchester, New Hampshire]].<ref>[http://www.newhampshire.com/nh-people/adam-sandler-biography.aspx \"Adam Sandler donates $1&nbsp;million to Manchester charity.\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818203545/http://www.newhampshire.com/nh-people/adam-sandler-biography.aspx |date=August 18, 2010 }} newhampshire.com.</ref> The same year, he donated $2,100 to former [[New York City]] Republican mayor [[Rudy Giuliani presidential campaign, 2008|Rudy Giuliani's presidential campaign]].\n\n== Filmography ==\n''This is a partial list of Sandler's film and television work. For the complete list, see [[Adam Sandler filmography]].''\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* ''[[Going Overboard]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' (1990\u20131995)\n* ''[[Coneheads (film)|Coneheads]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Airheads]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Billy Madison]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Happy Gilmore]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[The Wedding Singer]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[The Waterboy]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Big Daddy (1999 film)|Big Daddy]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Little Nicky]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Punch-Drunk Love]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Mr. Deeds]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Anger Management (film)|Anger Management]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[50 First Dates]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[The Longest Yard (2005 film)|The Longest Yard]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Reign Over Me]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[You Don't Mess with the Zohan]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Bedtime Stories (film)|Bedtime Stories]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Funny People]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Grown Ups (film)|Grown Ups]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Just Go with It]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Jack and Jill (2011 film)|Jack and Jill]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Hotel Transylvania]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Grown Ups 2]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Blended (film)|Blended]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Pixels (2015 film)|Pixels]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Hotel Transylvania 2]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[The Ridiculous 6]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[The Meyerowitz Stories|The Meyerowitz Stories (New and Selected)]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Hotel Transylvania 3: Summer Vacation]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Murder Mystery (film)|Murder Mystery]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Uncut Gems]]'' (2019)\n}}\n\n== Discography ==\n[[File:Adam Sandler footprint.jpg|thumb|Sandler's handprints and shoeprints in front of [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]], 2008]]\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Certification\n|-\n| 1993\n|''[[They're All Gonna Laugh at You!]]''\n| 2\u00d7 Platinum<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?artist=Sandler+Adam|title=RIAA - Gold & Platinum - Sandler, Adam|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1996\n|''[[What the Hell Happened to Me?]]''\n| 2\u00d7 Platinum<ref name=\"RIAA\"/>\n|-\n| 1997\n|''[[What's Your Name?]]''\n| Gold<ref name=\"RIAA\"/>\n|-\n| 1999\n|''[[Stan and Judy's Kid]]''\n| Gold<ref name=\"RIAA\"/>\n|-\n| 2004\n|''[[Shhh...Don't Tell]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n|''100% Fresh''\n|\n|-\n|}\n\nIn 2009 Sandler contributed the [[Neil Young]] cover \"[[Like a Hurricane (Neil Young song)|Like a Hurricane]]\" to ''[[Covered, A Revolution in Sound]]'' as part of Warner Brothers 50th Anniversary celebrations;<ref>{{cite web | url=http://neilyoungnews.thrasherswheat.org/2009/02/adam-sandler-covers-neil-youngs-like.html | title=Adam Sandler Covers Neil Young's \"Like a Hurricane\" | publisher=Thrasher's Wheat | work=Neil Young News blog | accessdate=March 18, 2019}}</ref> the song was performed on the ''[[David Letterman Show]]'' with a band that included, among others, [[Waddy Wachtel]],<ref>{{youtube|HT2ENDHIZ3c|Adam Sandler Performs Neil Young's \"Like a Hurricane\"}}</ref> who has appeared with Sandler on a number of occasions.<ref>{{youtube|1CD0C81D5D6E2142|Waddy Wachtel with Adam Sandler}}</ref>\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ \n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:2em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\" | Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:13em;\" | [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n\n!style=\"width:3em; font-size:90%\"|[[Hot 100]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|title=Adam Sandler Album & Song Chart History|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Adam Sandler|chart=Hot 100}}|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=December 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\n!style=\"width:3em; font-size:90%\"|[[Adult Top 40|Adult Pop]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|title=Adam Sandler Album & Song Chart History|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Adam Sandler|chart=Adult Pop Songs}}|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=December 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\n!style=\"width:3em; font-size:90%\"|[[Alternative Songs|Mod. Rock]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|title=Adam Sandler Album & Song Chart History|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Adam Sandler|chart=Alternative Songs}}|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"[[The Chanukah Song]]\"\n|1996\n| 80 || 28 || 25\n|\n* [[RIAA]]: Gold<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Adam+Sandler+#search_section|title=Gold & Platinum - RIAA|publisher=}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"[[The Thanksgiving Song]]\"\n|1997\n| \u2014 || 40 || 29\n|\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Adam Sandler}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{commons|Adam Sandler}}\n* {{Official|http://www.adamsandler.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|0001191}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Adam Sandler}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Adam Sandler|Awards for Adam Sandler]]\n|list =\n{{Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Actor}}\n{{Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay}}\n{{Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screen Combo}}\n{{IndependentSpiritBestMaleLead}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Comedic Performance}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Fight}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Kiss}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best On-Screen Duo}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Actor}}\n{{Teen Choice Award Choice Hissy Fit}}\n}}\n{{Happy Madison Productions}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sandler, Adam}}\n[[Category:Adam Sandler| ]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American writers]]\n[[Category:Actors from Manchester, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:American comedy musicians]]\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:American male comedy actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American sketch comedians]]\n[[Category:American stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Comedians from New York City]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award for Best Male Lead winners]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish American screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Jewish American comedians]]\n[[Category:Jewish male comedians]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:Manchester Central High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Singers from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Manchester, New Hampshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor, comedian, screenwriter, and producer}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name    = Adam Sandler\n| image   = Adam Sandler 2011 (Cropped).jpg\n| caption = Sandler receiving his star on the<br/> [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in February 2011\n| birth_name = Adam Richard Sandler\n| alias   = <!--This field is for official stage names, ''not'' for nicknames.-->\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|9|9}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], New York, U.S.\n| years_active = 1987\u2013present<ref>{{cite book|author1=Geoffrey M. Horn|title=Adam Sandler|date=2006|publisher=Gareth Stevens|isbn=0836842340|page=[https://archive.org/details/adamsandler0000horn/page/17 17]|url=https://archive.org/details/adamsandler0000horn|url-access=registration|quote=adam sandler 1987 cosby show.|accessdate=April 22, 2018}}</ref>\n| occupation = {{Flat list|\n*Actor\n*comedian\n*screenwriter\n*film producer\n*singer-songwriter}}\n| alma_mater = [[New York University]]\n| party =\n| spouse   = {{marriage|Jacqueline Titone|2003}}\n| children = 2\n| signature =\n| module = {{Infobox comedian|embed=yes\n| medium =  [[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]], [[film]], [[television]]\n| genre =\n| website  = {{url|adamsandler.com}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Adam Richard Sandler''' (born September 9, 1966) is an American actor, comedian, screenwriter, film producer, and singer-songwriter. After becoming a ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' cast member, he went on to star in many Hollywood feature films, which have combined grossed over $2 billion at the box office.<ref>{{cite web |title=People Index |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/?view=Actor&sort=sumgross&p=.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326160457/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/?view=Actor&sort=sumgross&p=.htm |archive-date=26 March 2018 |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Adam Sandler |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/person/126870401-Adam-Sandler#tab=summary |publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nSandler is best known for his comedic roles including ''[[Billy Madison]]'' (1995), ''[[Happy Gilmore]]'' (1996), ''[[The Waterboy]]'' (1998), ''[[The Wedding Singer]]'' (1998), ''[[Big Daddy (1999 film)|Big Daddy]]'' (1999), ''[[Mr. Deeds]]'' (2002), ''[[50 First Dates]]'' (2004), ''[[The Longest Yard (2005 film)|The Longest Yard]]'' (2005), ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]'' (2006), ''[[Grown Ups (film)|Grown Ups]]'' (2010), ''[[Just Go with It]]'' (2011), ''[[Grown Ups 2]]'' (2013), ''[[Blended (film)|Blended]]'' (2014), ''[[Murder Mystery (film)|Murder Mystery]]'' (2019). He also voices [[Count Dracula|Dracula]] in the [[Hotel Transylvania (franchise)|''Hotel Transylvania'' franchise]] (2012\u2013present).\n\nSome of his films, such as the widely panned ''[[Jack and Jill (2011 film)|Jack and Jill]]'', have been heavily criticized, culminating in a shared second place in the number of [[Raspberry Awards]] (three) and Raspberry Award nominations (11), in both cases second only to [[Sylvester Stallone]].\n\nSandler ventured into dramatic territory with his roles in ''[[Punch-Drunk Love]]'' (2002), ''[[Spanglish (film)|Spanglish]]'' (2004), ''[[Reign Over Me]]'' (2007), ''[[Funny People]]'' (2009), ''[[The Meyerowitz Stories|The Meyerowitz Stories (New and Selected)]]'' (2017), and ''[[Uncut Gems]]'' (2019), all of which earned him critical praise.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cea|first=Max|url=https://www.salon.com/2017/10/12/noah-baumbach-performs-a-miracle-adam-sandler-doesnt-suck-in-the-meyerowitz-stories/|title=Noah Baumbach performs a miracle: Adam Sandler doesn't suck in 'The Meyerowitz Stories' |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=October 12, 2017|accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nSandler was born in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], on September 9, 1966,<ref name=filmref /><ref name=biography.com>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/adam-sandler-9542505|title=Adam Sandler: Film Actor, Singer, Songwriter, Comedian, Screenwriter (1966\u2013)|website=[[Biography.com]]|publisher=[[A&E Networks]]| accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Monitor|newspaper=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=September 13, 2013|issue=1276|pages=28}}</ref> to Judith \"Judy\" (n\u00e9e Levine), a nursery school teacher, and Stanley Sandler, an electrical engineer.<ref name=\"filmref\">{{cite web| url = http://www.filmreference.com/film/70/Adam-Sandler.html |title=Adam Sandler Biography (1966?-)|publisher= FilmReference.com|accessdate=December 24, 2014 | quote=Full name, Adam Richard Sandler; born September 9, 1966 (some sources cite 1964)...}}</ref> His family is [[Jews|Jewish]] and descends from Russian Jewish immigrants on both sides.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jewishjournal.com/opinion/rob_eshman/180474/|title=Adam Sandler: \"I'm very pro-Israel\"|last=Eshman|first=Rob|date=December 15, 2015|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|Jewish Journal]]|accessdate=May 20, 2018|quote=\"I'm proud of being a Jew and that's what I am,\" Sandler said.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/3709985/Adam-Sandler-this-ones-for-the-kids.html|title=Adam Sandler: this one's for the kids|last=Hiscock|first=John|date=December 11, 2008|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=July 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/196117/adam-sandler-and-howard-stern-talk-jewish-shop|title= Adam Sandler and Howard Stern Talk Jewish Shop |first=Jonathan |last=Zalman |work=[[Tablet (magazine)|Tablet Magazine]]|date= December 22, 2015|accessdate= April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/i-didnt-get-into-movies-to-please-the-critics-adam-sandler-interview-8742294.html|title= 'I didn't get into movies to please the critics': Adam Sandler interview |work=[[The Independent]]|first=Emma |last=Jones |date= August 2, 2013|accessdate= April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=\u0413\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0413\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0430 |url=http://www.golos-ameriki.ru/content/just-go-with-it-2011-03-21-118361894/224464.html |title=\u041f\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u043a \u0410\u0434\u0430\u043c\u0430 \u0421\u044d\u043d\u0434\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0430 \u0438 \u0414\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0444\u0435\u0440 \u042d\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043d |website=Golos-ameriki.ru |date=March 21, 2011 |accessdate=June 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bh.org.il/blog-items/stars-of-david-10-jewish-hollywood-icons/|title=Let There Be Laughter \u2013 Jewish Humor Around the World|last=|first=|date=|website=Beit Hatfutsot|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> His [[patrilineal]] great-grandfather, Joseph Jacob Sandler, was born in  [[Pag\u0117giai Municipality]], [[Taurag\u0117 County]], [[Lithuania]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.geni.com/people/Joseph-Sandler/6000000029081386829?through=6000000038200170005 | title=Joseph Jacob Sandler (1878 - 1952) | publisher=[[Geni.com]] | date=January 20, 2019 | accessdate=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Sandler grew up in [[Manchester, New Hampshire]], after moving there at the age of six.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unionleader.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/99999999/NEWHAMPSHIRE09/110429372/-1/newhampshire09|title=Adam Sandler|work=UnionLeader.com}}</ref> He attended [[Manchester Central High School]]. As a teen, Sandler was in [[BBYO]], a Jewish youth group. Sandler graduated from [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]] in 1988.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.nyu.edu/alumni.magazine/issue10/10_culture_snl.html | title= Live From New York, It's... | publisher=[[New York University]] | work=NYU Alumni Magazine | date= Spring 2008 | accessdate=June 30, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100530061407/http://www.nyu.edu/alumni.magazine/issue10/10_culture_snl.html| archivedate= May 30, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Acting career ===\n[[File:Adamsandler(cannesPhotocall).jpg|thumb|Sandler at 2002 [[Cannes Film Festival]]]]\nEarly in his career, in 1987, Sandler played [[Theo Huxtable]]'s friend, Smitty, in ''[[The Cosby Show]]'' and the Stud Boy or Trivia Delinquent in the [[Game show|MTV game show]] ''[[Remote Control (game show)|Remote Control]]''. After his film debut ''[[Going Overboard]]'' in 1989, Sandler performed in comedy clubs, having first taken the stage at his brother's urging when he was 17. He was discovered by comedian [[Dennis Miller]], who caught Sandler's act in Los Angeles and recommended him to ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' producer [[Lorne Michaels]]. Sandler was hired as a writer for ''SNL'' in 1990 and became a featured player the following year, making a name for himself by performing amusing original songs on the show, including \"[[The Thanksgiving Song]]\" and \"[[The Chanukah Song]]\".<ref name=biography.com/> Sandler told [[Conan O'Brien]] on ''[[The Tonight Show with Conan O'Brien|The Tonight Show]]'' that [[NBC]] fired him and [[Chris Farley]] from the show in 1995, and played this up in his return to the show as a host in 2019.<ref name=\"Sandler fired\">{{cite news| url = http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/2010/01/21/2010-01-21_youre_not_alone_conan_obrien_adam_sandler_says_nbc_fired_him_and_chris_farley_fr.html | title= You're not alone, Conan O'Brien: Adam Sandler says NBC fired him and Chris Farley from 'SNL'| first= Joe |last=Dziemianowicz| work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] | location=New York City |date= January 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Adam Sandler's \"I Was Fired\" Monologue - SNL |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eghK5yMpNuc |publisher=SNL}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Adam Sandler appeared in the film ''[[Coneheads (film)|Coneheads]]'' with Chris Farley, [[David Spade]], [[Dan Aykroyd]], [[Phil Hartman]], and [[Jane Curtin]]. In 1994, he co-starred in ''[[Airheads]]'' with [[Brendan Fraser]] and [[Steve Buscemi]]. He starred in ''[[Billy Madison]]'' (1995) playing a grown man repeating grades 1\u201312 to earn back his father's respect and the right to inherit his father's multimillion-dollar hotel empire. The film was successful at the box office despite negative reviews. He followed this film with ''[[Bulletproof (1996 film)|Bulletproof]]'' (1996), and the financially successful comedies ''Happy Gilmore'' (1996) and ''The Wedding Singer'' (1998). He was initially cast in the bachelor party\u2013themed comedy/thriller ''[[Very Bad Things]]'' (1998) but had to back out due to his involvement in ''[[The Waterboy]]'' (1998), one of his first hits.\n\nAlthough his earliest films did not receive favorable critical attention, he started to receive more positive reviews, beginning with ''Punch-Drunk Love'' in 2002. [[Roger Ebert]]'s review of ''Punch-Drunk Love'' concluded that Sandler had been wasted in earlier films with poorly written scripts and characters with no development.<ref>Ebert, Roger. [http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20021018/REVIEWS/210180308/1023 \"Punch-Drunk Love.\"] ''Chicago Sun-Times''. October 18, 2002.</ref> Sandler has moved outside the genre of slapstick comedy to take on more serious roles, such as the aforementioned ''[[Punch-Drunk Love]]'', for which he was nominated for a [[Golden Globe]], and [[Mike Binder]]'s ''[[Reign Over Me]]'' (2007), a drama about a man who loses his entire family during the [[September 11 attacks]], and then struggles to rekindle a friendship with his old college roommate ([[Don Cheadle]]).\n\nHe starred alongside friend [[Kevin James]] in the film ''[[I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry]]'' (2007), and headlined ''[[You Don't Mess with the Zohan]]'' (2008). The latter film was written by Sandler, [[Judd Apatow]], and [[Robert Smigel]], and directed by [[Dennis Dugan]].\n\n[[File:Adam Sandler 6818.jpg|thumb|left|Sandler in [[Berlin]] in 2009]]\nSandler starred along with [[Keri Russell]] and English comedian [[Russell Brand]] in [[Adam Shankman]]'s fantasy film ''[[Bedtime Stories (film)|Bedtime Stories]]'' (2008), as a stressed hotel maintenance worker whose bedtime stories he reads to his niece and nephew begin to come true. It marked as Sandler's first family film and first film under the [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney]] banner.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=19719 |title=Adam Sandler's Bedtime Stories Come True| website=ComingSoon.net | date= April 4, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Sandler starred in Judd Apatow's third directorial feature ''[[Funny People]]''. The film was released on July 31, 2009.<ref>{{cite news | author=Michael Fleming | title = Trio joins Judd Apatow film |work=Variety | date = June 11, 2008 | url = https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117987337.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | accessdate=June 13, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080709034441/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117987337.html?categoryid=13&cs=1| archivedate=July 9, 2008| url-status= live}}</ref> Following the release of ''Funny People'', it, along with ''Punch-Drunk Love'' were cited in the June 2010 announcement that Sandler was one of 135 people (including 20 actors) invited to join the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2010/20100625.html | title= Academy Invites 135 to Membership | publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] | work=[[Press release]] | date= June 25, 2010 | location= Beverly Hills, CA | accessdate=June 29, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100630164148/http://www.oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2010/20100625.html| archivedate= June 30, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nSandler appeared in ''[[Grown Ups (film)|Grown Ups]]'', alongside Kevin James, [[Chris Rock]], [[Rob Schneider]], and David Spade. Sandler and ''Dickie Roberts'' scribe Fred Wolf wrote the script and Dennis Dugan directed the film.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117999951.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | title = Columbia pic gets Sandler and friends |work=Variety | date = February 10, 2009 | accessdate=February 12, 2009 | first=Tatiana | last=Siegel| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090213130229/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117999951.html?categoryid=13&cs=1| archivedate= February 13, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nSandler starred with [[Jennifer Aniston]] in the 2011 romantic comedy film ''[[Just Go with It]]''. Sandler also voiced a capuchin monkey in Kevin James's ''[[Zookeeper (film)|Zookeeper]]'', released on July 8, 2011. In 2012, he starred in ''[[That's My Boy (2012 film)|That's My Boy]]'', as a man who fathered a son ([[Andy Samberg]]) with his teacher in high school.\n\nSandler starred with [[Drew Barrymore]] in the [[Warner Bros.]] romantic comedy ''[[Blended (film)|Blended]]'', which was filmed in [[South Africa]], and was released on May 23, 2014.\n\nIn 2013, he guest starred in the [[Disney Channel Original Series]] ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'' as himself. He and [[Cameron Boyce]] previously worked together in ''Grown Ups'' and ''[[Grown Ups 2]]''. The episode is titled \"Punched Dumped Love\". Sandler co-starred in the drama film ''[[Men, Women & Children (film)|Men, Women & Children]]'' (2014), directed by [[Jason Reitman]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Toronto: Jason Reitman Lining Up His Next Film|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/toronto-jason-reitman-lining-up-620958|accessdate=19 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=September 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|publisher=Paramount Pictures|title=Production Begins on Jason Reitman's Men, Women & Children|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=112527|accessdate=December 19, 2013|via=ComingSoon.net|date=December 16, 2013}}</ref> He was considered for the voice of Rocket Raccoon in Marvel's ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' but [[Bradley Cooper]] was cast instead.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ifc.com/2013/01/jim-carrey-adam-sandler-guardians-of-the-galaxy| publisher=[[IFC (U.S. TV channel)|IFC]] | title= Jim Carrey and Adam Sandler Being Considered For \"Guardians of the Galaxy\"| accessdate= October 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSandler's recent comedy films, including ''Grown Ups'' and ''Grown Ups 2'', have received strongly negative reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/grown-ups-2-best-lines-584676|title='Grown Ups 2': The Best Lines from the Worst Reviews|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=July 12, 2013|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> In reviewing the latter, critic Mark Olsen of ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' remarked that Sandler had become the antithesis of [[Judd Apatow]]; he was instead \"the white [[Tyler Perry]]: smart enough to know better, savvy enough to do it anyway, lazy enough not to care.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-grown-ups-2-review-20130712-story.html|title='Review: 'Grown Ups 2' refuses to leave the sandbox|work=The Los Angeles Times|date=July 11, 2013|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Sandler released his last theatrical film ''[[Pixels (2015 film)|Pixels]]'', based on French director Patrick Jean's [[Pixels (2010 film)|2010 short film of the same name]], before transitioning into a distribution deal with [[Netflix]]. His first original film for Netflix was the Western comedy film ''[[The Ridiculous 6]]''. Despite being universally panned by critics,<ref name=\"rotten\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_ridiculous_six/ |title= The Ridiculous Six (2015) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=December 15, 2015}}</ref> on January 6, 2016, it was announced by Netflix that the film had been viewed more times in 30 days than any other movie in Netflix history.<ref>[https://variety.com/2016/film/news/adam-sandlers-ridiculous-six-is-making-history-for-netflix-1201673572 Adam Sandle'\u2019s 'Ridiculous Six' Is Making History for Netflix] ''Variety.com''.</ref> He released three additional films on Netflix between 2016 and 2018: ''[[The Do-Over]]'', ''[[Sandy Wexler]]'' and ''[[The Week Of]]''.\n\nHe returned to dramatic territory in 2017 with ''[[The Meyerowitz Stories]]'', with his performance receiving favorable notices from critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2017/10/12/noah-baumbach-performs-a-miracle-adam-sandler-doesnt-suck-in-the-meyerowitz-stories/|title=Noah Baumbach performs a miracle: Adam Sandler doesn't suck in \"The Meyerowitz Stories\"|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|date=October 12, 2017|accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2019, Sandler made his first appearance as host of SNL, ending the episode with a tribute to his friend and fellow former cast member [[Chris Farley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/snl-adam-sandler-hosts-first-time-pays-tribute-chris-farley-1207490|title='SNL': Adam Sandler Hosts For First Time, Pays Tribute to Chris Farley|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, Sandler starred in the crime thriller drama ''[[Uncut Gems]]'', directed by the [[Safdie brothers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Adam Sandler Shows Off His Acting Chops In \u2018Uncut Gems\u2019 Trailer |url=https://digg.com/video/adam-sandler-uncut-gems-trailer |publisher=Digg |accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref> The movie and Sandler's acting received acclaim and many end of year awards from critics, who noted this role as a career best for Sandler.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/uncut-gems-review-adam-sandler-safdie-brothers-cast-director-a9276151.html|title='Uncut Gems review: The best performance of Adam Sandler\u2019s career'|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/10/04/uncut-gems-review-the-best-movie-of-adam-sandlers-career/|title=\u2018Uncut Gems\u2019 review: The best movie of Adam Sandler\u2019s career|publisher=New York Post|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Happy Madison Productions ===\n[[File:Adam Sandler (cropped).jpg|thumb|Sandler at a press conference for ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]'' in 2005]]\nSandler formed his film production company, [[Happy Madison Productions]],<ref name=\"happy\">[http://www.adamsandler.com/index.php?section=happy \"Happy Madison.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051118222008/http://www.adamsandler.com/index.php?section=happy |date=November 18, 2005 }} AdamSandler.com. Accessed October 9, 2008.</ref> in 1999, first producing fellow ''SNL'' alumnus [[Rob Schneider]]'s film ''[[Deuce Bigalow: Male Gigolo]]''. The company has produced most of Sandler's subsequent films to date. The majority of the company's films have received negative reviews from critics, with three considered to be among the [[List of films considered the worst|worst ever made]]<ref>[https://www.metacritic.com/feature/adam-sandler-all-films-considered Adam Sandler: All Films Considered] Metacritic. Accessed April 21, 2015.</ref> yet most have performed well at box office.\n\nOthers who frequently appear in Sandler films include [[David Spade]], [[Kevin James]], [[Steve Buscemi]], [[Chris Rock]], [[John Turturro]], [[Peter Dante]], [[Allen Covert]], [[Jonathan Loughran]], and [[Jon Lovitz]].\n\nIn 2014, Netflix announced a four-movie deal with Adam Sandler and Happy Madison Productions.<ref>{{Cite web|title = With Four New Adam Sandler Films, Netflix Takes Aim at Theaters - NYTimes.com|url = http://mobile.nytimes.com/2014/10/02/business/media/with-four-new-adam-sandler-films-netflix-takes-aim-at-theaters.html|website = mobile.nytimes.com|accessdate = 2015-12-13}}</ref>\n\nThe company is located on the Sony/[[Columbia Pictures]] lot in [[Culver City, California]].\n\n==Public image==\nSandler has been referenced multiple times in various media, including in the TV shows ''[[The Simpsons]]'' in the episode \"[[Monty Can't Buy Me Love]]\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bbc.adactio.com/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season10/page20.shtml|title=Monty Can't Buy Me|website=[[BBC Online]]|date=September 2005|access-date=August 11, 2017}}</ref> in ''[[Family Guy]]'' in the episode \"[[Stew-Roids]]\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ign.com/articles/2009/04/27/family-guy-stew-roids-review|title=Family Guy: \"Stew-Roids\" Review|website=[[IGN]]|first=Ahsan|last=Haque|date=April 27, 2009|access-date=August 11, 2017}}</ref> and in ''[[South Park]]'' in the episode \"[[You're Getting Old]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2011/06/09/south-park-watch-the-tao-of-poo/|title=South Park Watch: The Tao of Poo|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |first=James|last=Poniewozik|date=June 9, 2011|access-date=August 11, 2017}}</ref> He was also referenced in the video game ''[[Half-Life: Opposing Force]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vgfacts.com/trivia/6729/|title=Half-Life: Opposing Force|publisher=[[Did You Know Gaming?#VGFacts|VGFacts]]|author=\"RetroRex\"|access-date=August 11, 2017|quote=There is a hidden message on the upper skybox texture in the V-22 osprey g-man sequence. It reads \"HACK HACK HACK ALL DAY LONG. HACK HACK HACK WHILE I SING THIS SONG\". This is a reference to the Adam Sandler song \"The Beating Of A High School Janitor.}}</ref> The [[HBO]] series ''[[Animals (U.S. TV series)|Animals]]'' episode \"The Trial\" features a mock court case to decide whether Sandler or [[Jim Carrey]] is a better comedian.\n\n==Personal life==\nOn <!--Sunday--> June 22, 2003, Sandler married model-actress Jacqueline Titone.<ref name=married>{{cite news|url=https://siouxcityjournal.com/entertainment/adam-sandler-marries-model-actress-jackie-titone/article_268844b3-7fc8-5d98-af1c-36ff72ea3bdd.html|title=Adam Sandler marries model-actress Jackie Titone|agency=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[Sioux City Journal]]|date=<!--Tuesday-->June 24, 2003|accessdate=March 26, 2019|archivedate=March 26, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326152430/https://siouxcityjournal.com/entertainment/adam-sandler-marries-model-actress-jackie-titone/article_268844b3-7fc8-5d98-af1c-36ff72ea3bdd.html|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Titone had [[Conversion to Judaism|converted]] to Sandler's religion, Judaism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/nydn-features/numbers-drew-adam-article-1.643235 |title=By The Numbers Drew & Adam |work=New York Daily News |date=February 17, 2004 |accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref> She makes frequent appearances in her husband's films. The couple have two daughters, born in May 2006,<ref>{{cite web|last=Wihlborg |first=Ulrica|url=https://people.com/celebrity/adam-sandler-wife-have-a-baby/|title=Adam Sandler, Wife Have a Baby|work=People|date=May 7, 2006|accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> and November 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE4AB18Q20081112|title=Adam Sandler and wife have second daughter|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=November 12, 2008|accessdate=February 3, 2018}}</ref> who also make frequent appearances in his films.\n\nSandler is a registered [[Republican Party (U.S.)|Republican]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Adam Sandler\u2019s Religion and Political Views |url=https://hollowverse.com/adam-sandler/ |website=hollowverse.com |accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref> In 2007, Sandler made a $1 million donation to the [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America]] in his hometown, [[Manchester, New Hampshire]].<ref>[http://www.newhampshire.com/nh-people/adam-sandler-biography.aspx \"Adam Sandler donates $1&nbsp;million to Manchester charity.\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818203545/http://www.newhampshire.com/nh-people/adam-sandler-biography.aspx |date=August 18, 2010 }} newhampshire.com.</ref> The same year, he donated $2,100 to former [[New York City]] Republican mayor [[Rudy Giuliani presidential campaign, 2008|Rudy Giuliani's presidential campaign]].\n\n== Filmography ==\n''This is a partial list of Sandler's film and television work. For the complete list, see [[Adam Sandler filmography]].''\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* ''[[Going Overboard]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' (1990\u20131995)\n* ''[[Coneheads (film)|Coneheads]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Airheads]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Billy Madison]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Happy Gilmore]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[The Wedding Singer]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[The Waterboy]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Big Daddy (1999 film)|Big Daddy]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Little Nicky]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Punch-Drunk Love]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Mr. Deeds]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Anger Management (film)|Anger Management]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[50 First Dates]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[The Longest Yard (2005 film)|The Longest Yard]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Reign Over Me]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[You Don't Mess with the Zohan]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Bedtime Stories]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Funny People]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Grown Ups (film)|Grown Ups]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Just Go with It]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Jack and Jill (2011 film)|Jack and Jill]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Hotel Transylvania]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Grown Ups 2]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Blended (film)|Blended]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Pixels (2015 film)|Pixels]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Hotel Transylvania 2]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[The Ridiculous 6]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[The Meyerowitz Stories|The Meyerowitz Stories (New and Selected)]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Hotel Transylvania 3: Summer Vacation]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Murder Mystery (film)|Murder Mystery]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Uncut Gems]]'' (2019)\n}}\n\n== Discography ==\n[[File:Adam Sandler footprint.jpg|thumb|Sandler's handprints and shoeprints in front of [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]], 2008]]\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Certification\n|-\n| 1993\n|''[[They're All Gonna Laugh at You!]]''\n| 2\u00d7 Platinum<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?artist=Sandler+Adam|title=RIAA - Gold & Platinum - Sandler, Adam|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1996\n|''[[What the Hell Happened to Me?]]''\n| 2\u00d7 Platinum<ref name=\"RIAA\"/>\n|-\n| 1997\n|''[[What's Your Name?]]''\n| Gold<ref name=\"RIAA\"/>\n|-\n| 1999\n|''[[Stan and Judy's Kid]]''\n| Gold<ref name=\"RIAA\"/>\n|-\n| 2004\n|''[[Shhh...Don't Tell]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n|''100% Fresh''\n|\n|-\n|}\n\nIn 2009 Sandler contributed the [[Neil Young]] cover \"[[Like a Hurricane (Neil Young song)|Like a Hurricane]]\" to ''[[Covered, A Revolution in Sound]]'' as part of Warner Brothers 50th Anniversary celebrations;<ref>{{cite web | url=http://neilyoungnews.thrasherswheat.org/2009/02/adam-sandler-covers-neil-youngs-like.html | title=Adam Sandler Covers Neil Young's \"Like a Hurricane\" | publisher=Thrasher's Wheat | work=Neil Young News blog | accessdate=March 18, 2019}}</ref> the song was performed on the ''[[David Letterman Show]]'' with a band that included, among others, [[Waddy Wachtel]],<ref>{{youtube|HT2ENDHIZ3c|Adam Sandler Performs Neil Young's \"Like a Hurricane\"}}</ref> who has appeared with Sandler on a number of occasions.<ref>{{youtube|1CD0C81D5D6E2142|Waddy Wachtel with Adam Sandler}}</ref>\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ \n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:2em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\" | Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:13em;\" | [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n\n!style=\"width:3em; font-size:90%\"|[[Hot 100]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|title=Adam Sandler Album & Song Chart History|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Adam Sandler|chart=Hot 100}}|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=December 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\n!style=\"width:3em; font-size:90%\"|[[Adult Top 40|Adult Pop]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|title=Adam Sandler Album & Song Chart History|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Adam Sandler|chart=Adult Pop Songs}}|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=December 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\n!style=\"width:3em; font-size:90%\"|[[Alternative Songs|Mod. Rock]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|title=Adam Sandler Album & Song Chart History|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Adam Sandler|chart=Alternative Songs}}|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"[[The Chanukah Song]]\"\n|1996\n| 80 || 28 || 25\n|\n* [[RIAA]]: Gold<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Adam+Sandler+#search_section|title=Gold & Platinum - RIAA|publisher=}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"[[The Thanksgiving Song]]\"\n|1997\n| \u2014 || 40 || 29\n|\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Adam Sandler}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{commons|Adam Sandler}}\n* {{Official|http://www.adamsandler.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|0001191}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Adam Sandler}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Adam Sandler|Awards for Adam Sandler]]\n|list =\n{{Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Actor}}\n{{Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay}}\n{{Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screen Combo}}\n{{IndependentSpiritBestMaleLead}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Comedic Performance}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Fight}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Kiss}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best On-Screen Duo}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Best Actor}}\n{{Teen Choice Award Choice Hissy Fit}}\n}}\n{{Happy Madison Productions}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sandler, Adam}}\n[[Category:Adam Sandler| ]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American co