{"title_page": "PJ Masks", "text_new": "{{use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{use American English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = PJ Masks\n| image                    = PJ-Masks-logo-2.png\n| caption                  = Current logo of the series\n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Action film|Action]]\n*[[Superhero film|Superhero]]\n*[[Science fiction]]\n*[[Drama]]\n}}\n| creator                  = Romuald Racioppo\n| based_on                 = {{based on|''[[Les Pyjamasques]]''|Romuald Racioppo}}\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n*Christian De Vita\n*Wilson Dos Santos\n*Florante Mari Villareal\n*Chad V. Vidanes\n}}\n| voices                   = {{Plainlist|\n*Roman Lutterotti\n*[[Addison Holley]]\n*[[Claire Corlett]]\n*Simon Pirso\n*Jacob Soley\n*Brianna Daguanno\n}}\n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = {{Plainlist|\n*Eric Renwart\n*[[David Freedman (screenwriter)|David Freedman]]\n}}\n| composer                 = Fabrice Aboulker<br />Jean-Francois Berger\n| country                  = {{Plainlist|\n*France\n*United Kingdom\n}}\n| language                 = {{Plainlist|\n*French\n*English\n}}\n| num_seasons              = 5<!-- season the last aired episode belongs to -->\n| num_episodes             = 66<!-- number released or aired --> (and 41 shorts)\n| list_episodes            = List of PJ Masks episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n*Olivier Dumont\n*Laura Clunie\n*Beth Gardiner\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n*Guillaume Hellouin\n*Corinne Kouper\n}}\n| runtime                  = 24 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Entertainment One]]\n*Frog Box Productions\n*[[TeamTO]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teamto.com/en/les-productions/les-productions-executives/pyjamasques|title=PJmasks|work=[[TeamTO]]|accessdate=December 1, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402113704/http://www.teamto.com/en/les-productions/les-productions-executives/pyjamasques|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref> (Season 2-present)\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Entertainment One]]\n| network                  = [[France 5]] (France)<br>[[Disney Junior]]\n| picture_format           = [[HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n| audio_format             = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2015|9|18}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| website                  = http://pjmasks.com\n| production_website       = \n}}\n'''''PJ Masks''''' (French: Pyjamasques) is a French-British [[Computer animated|CGI-animated]] [[Superhero fiction|superhero]] [[children's television series]] produced by Frog Box, [[Entertainment One|Entertainment One UK Limited]], [[TeamTO]], with the participation of [[France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions]] and [[Disney Junior]]. The series is based on the ''[[Les Pyjamasques]]'' book series by Romuald Racioppo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awn.com/news/pj-masks-sees-strong-us-debut|title=\u2018PJ Masks\u2019 Sees Strong U.S. Debut|author=Jennifer Wolfe|work=[[Animation World Network]]|date=October 2, 2015|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref> [[Disney Channels Worldwide]]'s Disney Junior channels broadcast ''PJ Masks'' worldwide, while [[France 5]] airs the series in its original home country of [[France]]; it also airs on [[Tiny Pop]] in the [[United Kingdom|UK]], [[ABC Kids (Australia)|ABC Kids]] in [[Australia]], [[Rai YoYo|RAI YoYo]] in [[Italy]], [[TV Cultura]] in [[Brazil]], and [[Televisa]] in [[Mexico]]. The series debuted on Disney Junior in the [[United States]] on 18 September 2015, on France 5 on 18 December 2015, and on [[Disney Junior (Canadian TV channel)|Disney Junior]] in [[Canada]] on 7 February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/programming/disney-channel-disney-junior-debut-pj-masks-sept-18/143830|title=Disney Channel, Disney Junior to Debut \u2018PJ Masks\u2019 Sept. 18|author=Luke McCord|work=Broadcasting & Cable|date=September 2, 2015|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref> In June 2016, a second season, consisting of another 52 11-minute segments, was announced;<ref name=\"THR\" /> it began airing on 15 January 2017. On 19 April 2019, the first episode of the third season was aired. The start of the fourth season was announced to air in April 2020, but will probably air in May instead.\n\nThe first two seasons of the show became available to stream on [[Disney+]] on its launch, November 12, 2019, with seasons 3, 4 and 5 being available after their finales have aired.\n\nOn 5 May 2019, [[Hasbro]] acquired Entertainment One for a $3.8 billion deal,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/12/30/hasbro-entertainment-one-eone-peppa-pig-pj-masks-ricky-zoom-movies-television/|title=Hasbro's Toy Box Is Bigger Than Ever With $3.8 Billion Entertainment One Takeover|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> making the series under the ownership of [[Hasbro]].\n\n==Premise==\nAmaya, Greg, and Connor become the [[fictional character|fictional]] superhero team PJ Masks when night falls in order to fight enemies and rivals such as Romeo, Luna Girl, Night Ninja, and Motsuki, The Wolfy Kids and Octobella to keep them from ruining people's day. Amaya becomes Owlette (an [[owl]]), Greg becomes Gekko (a [[lizard]]), and Connor becomes Catboy (a [[cat]]).\n\n==Characters==\n===PJ Masks===\n'''PJ Masks''' (known as \"PJs\" for short) is the titular superhero team that fights crime at night to keep it from ruining people's days. Their catchphrase when planning to go fight their enemies is \"PJ Masks, we're on our way. Into the night, to save the day!\" Their base is hidden in a totem-like structure in the park, called their \"HQ\", which also houses a crystal that grants them their abilities. When the villains are defeated, their victory catchphrase is \"PJ Masks, all shout hooray, 'cause in the night, we saved the day!\" Among its members and allies are:\n\n====Members====\n* Connor / Catboy (voiced by [[Jacob Ewaniuk]] in Season 1, Jacob Ursomarzo in Season 2-\"Best Friends Forever\", and Roman Lutterotti in \"Meet An Yu\"-present) \u2013 Connor is a blue-eyed boy with brown hair. When he transforms, he wears a blue [[cat]] costume with cat ears and a thin feline tail.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Catboy and the Shrinker|series=PJ Masks|quote=I'm not that little, and I can still be your leader.}}</ref> He has super-hearing using Cat Ears, can leap high and far using Super Cat Jump (or \"Super Cat Leap\"), and sprints fast using Super Cat Speed,<ref name=ep2>{{cite episode|series=PJ Masks|number=2}}</ref> or just Super Speed.<ref name=SuperMS>{{cite episode|title=Owlette and the Moonball|series=PJ Masks|minutes=21|quote=We need to play as a team. Gekko, use your Super Muscles, Catboy, use your Super Speed, and I'll use my Owl Wing Wind!}}</ref> Starting in season 2, he also has Super Cat Stripes. When on a mission, he sometimes likes to narrate his actions. His main flaws are his [[impulsiveness]] and his need to control, flaws that can be exploited by the team's opponents. He is the only member of the team that [[Aquaphobia|hates water]]. His vehicle is the Cat Car, which is located in the middle segment of the PJ Masks' tower. It can launch blue hairballs at any obstacle. His bedroom is on the second floor of a blue-roofed blue-doored house next to Amaya's house. Unlike Amaya and Greg, Connor is the only one without a pet.\n** Kitten Boy (voiced by Jacob Ursomarzo in \"Terrible Two-Some\", Roman Lutterotti in \"Big Sister Motsuki\") \u2013 The baby-fied version of Catboy who appeared in \"Terrible Two-Some\". Unlike Chicklette, he acts like a [[kitten]]. Whenever he uses his super cat speed, he exclaims \u201cSuper Cat Speed, and whoosh!\u201d He and Chicklette returned in \"Big Sister Motsuki\".\n* Amaya / Owlette (voiced by [[Addison Holley]]) \u2013 Amaya is a brown-eyed girl who wears red glasses, as well as PJ Masks' only female member besides An Yu. She has dark brown hair with a pink, wing-shaped hair clip. When she transforms, she wears a red [[owl]] costume with a dark red [[facial disc]] and a cape made of artificial feathers (dubbed her \"Super Owl Wings\"), which helps her fly. She also loses her glasses and presumably wears contact lenses. Her eyes also become an intense, blood-red color that matches her suit. She has Owl Eyes that let her see things that are far away up close, and she also has Super Owl Wing Wind, or just Owl Wing Wind (She also occasionally has super strength). Starting in season 2, she also has Super Owl Feathers, which sometimes form a Super Feather Shield. Despite being a member of PJ Masks, as well as being as adorable and likable as her teammates, she is also rude and unlikable at times (most notably in \"Glowy Moths\", where she even teamed up with Luna to get revenge on Romeo). While she doesn't mind water as Amaya, as seen in \"Catboy's Cloudy Crisis\", she is rarely soaked as Owlette. But when she is, the feathers on her suit get really soggy.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Catboy's Two Wheeled Wonder|series=PJ Masks|quote=I'm okay. But he got all my feathers wet.}}</ref> During PJ Masks Takeover Weekend on Disney Junior, she is revealed to also be the smartest member of the team. Her vehicle is the Owl-Glider, which can also do a \"Super Owl Wing Wind\". It is located in the top segment of the PJ Masks' tower. Her bedroom is on the third floor of a red-roofed red-doored home with a walled-in yard between Connor and Greg's houses. Amaya owns a bird named Birdie. Despite the fact that she is Connor's best friend, she flirts with him for convincing him to give the extra ticket to her (much to Greg/Gekko's chagrin) in \"Catboy's Tricky Ticket\". Owlette is male in the books.\n** Chicklette (also voiced by Addison Holley) \u2013 The baby-fied version of Owlette who appeared in \"Terrible Two-Some\". Whenever she uses her super owl wing wind, she exclaims \u201cSuper Owly Wingy-Wind!\u201d She and Kitten Boy returned in \"Big Sister Motsuki\".\n* Greg / Gekko (voiced by [[Kyle Harrison Breitkopf]] in Season 1-Season 3 and the short films and [[Claire Corlett]] in \"HQ Tour\" and Season 4-present) \u2013 Greg is a green-eyed, blonde-haired boy. When he transforms, he wears a green [[lizard]] costume with a thick reptilian tail and fins on top of his head. His powers are: Super Gekko Camouflage to go invisible or blend into the environment around him, Super Gekko Muscles (aka Super Muscles<ref name=SuperMS/>) to lift heavy things, like the HQ, Super Lizard Grip to climb walls or anchor himself to stop vehicles, and Super Lizard Water Run to walk on water.<ref name=ep2/> He has exhibited enough strength to lift a mobile laboratory (namely Romeo's) off the ground. Starting in season 2, he also has Super Lizard Shields, which can create shields. He is the only semi-aquatic member of the PJ Masks. His vehicle is the Gekko-Mobile, which is also a submersible vehicle that can travel underwater and can also ride up & over buildings via land on tank treads; it is slower than the Cat-Car. His vehicle is located in the bottom segment of the PJ Masks' tower. The vehicle has abilities similar to him, with a \"Gekko-Mobile Camouflage\" letting it blend in with surroundings. His bedroom is on the second floor of a green-roofed green-doored house next to Amaya's. Greg has a gecko named Lionel. In seasons 1\u20132, an ongoing joke about how he \"can't think of a rhyme\" was finished in \"Pirates Ahoy!\" when he sang with Owlette/Amaya, where they were singing about each other and he thought of a rhyme for the relationship of them both in that segment. It is hinted that he has a slim crush on Amaya/Owlette, but some fans believe that he has a crush on Luna Girl. He is also Connor's best friend and is treated like a little brother.\n** Baby Gekko (voiced by Kyle Harrison Breitkopf) \u2013 The baby-fied version of Gekko who appeared in \"Big Sister Motsuki\". Unlike the other baby PJs, he is the only one who never speaks by himself and usually only speaks in unison with the other babies. However, at one point, he did say \"Muscle Wuscles!\" when he used his Super Gekko Muscles.\n* PJ Robot (voiced by Juan Luis Bonilla) \u2013 A robot that Romeo created to infiltrate the PJ Masks HQ. However, PJ Robot decided to be a PJ Mask rather than a villain's sidekick. He joined the PJ Masks Team in Season 2. He spends most of his time inside HQ as mission control for the PJ Masks. He doesn't speak much, but when he does, it usually comes out as robotic gibberish that only the PJ Masks and Romeo can understand. He is the creator of the PJ Seeker.\n\n====Allies====\n* Teeny Weeny Ninjalino (actor unknown) \u2013 A tiny and cute ninja from \"Catboy and the Teeny Weeny Ninjalino\", who was supposed to spy on the PJ Masks but won Owlette and Gekko's affection. Catboy (who was too quick to judge him, but later became his friend after being unstuck from the Owl Glider by him) kept wanting to get rid of him, and convinced his teammates to do so as well. He returned in \"Race Up Mystery Mountain\", where he mostly interacted with Gekko. In \"A Teeny Weeny Problem\", Teeny turned on his master. But in \"The Disappearing Ninjas\" he returned to his master's side.\n** The Splat Monster (actor unknown) \u2013 The alternate form Teeny took in the episode of the same name, where he turned into a Splat Monster when he touched the transforming splat in the Mystery Mountain cave. The Teeny Weeny Ninjalino was restored to normal by An Yu. This form returned in \"A Teeny Weeny Problem\" and again in \"The Disappearing Ninjas.\"\n* Armadylan (voiced by Max Calinescu in Season 2-\"Armadylan Zen\", Christian Perri in \"Arma-Leader\"-present) \u2013 An [[armadillo]]-like boy who wants to be a hero, but his being inexperienced causes him to mess up. He first meets the PJ Masks in \"Meet Armadylan\" and became an official member of the PJ Masks team in the episode \"PJ Dylan\". Armadylan's powers are his Thunder Thump to shake the ground, super strength to lift any heavy objects, like Gekko, the Rolling Thunder to roll himself up into a ball to attack his opponents and he can also dig to go underneath the ground. He is mostly mistaken by Romeo and Night Ninja for an anteater and/or an aardvark instead of an armadillo. He has a crush on either Rip or Octobella.\n* Captain Smartypants (voiced by Carter Thorne) \u2013 A young scientist who is the good version of Romeo. He helps Gekko change his teammates back to normal before Robot changes him back to his usual, evil self in \"Gekko and the Opposite Ray\".\n* An Yu (voiced by Kari Wong) \u2013 A samurai girl who uses her bo staff as a weapon or to fly; it also turns into a magic flute. She also turned out to be the human form of the Dragon from the Dragon Gong, as hinted by the gold dragon head on her headdress. She first appears in her human form in the season 3 episode \"Meet An Yu\". An Yu was a loner{{snd}}she attempted to face Night Ninja (from the episode \"Meet An Yu\") alone without the PJ Masks{{snd}}but they helped her out anyway, and she has occasionally helped them out in return. An Yu's powers mostly work on Mystery Mountain, and she can't use her magic flute in the town either, as seen in \"A Teeny Weeny Problem\".\n*Lionel (actor unknown) \u2013 a small gekko who is the pet of Gekko, he normally appeared when the PJ Masks are transforming. He then had a major role in \"Lionel-saurs.\" when Romeo made him huge.\n*[[Santa Claus|Santa ]](voiced by [[Ron Pardo]]) - Santa is the jolly man who appeared in \"The PJ Masks Save Christmas.\" where he teamed up with the PJ Masks to stop Romeo from running [[Christmas]]. He appears with a long beard and was not as fat as the other adaptations of him.\n* Newton (actor unknown at the moment) \u2013 An upcoming character who is set to appear in season 4, and was first seen in a storyboard video for the season's 14th episode. He has star powers. He is likely to be the first hero to appear in both daytime and nighttime.\n\n===Villains===\n* Romeo (voiced by Alex Thorne in Season 1, Carter Thorne in the short films and Season 2-\"Owlette Slips Up\", Simon Pirso in \"Motsuki the Best\"-present) \u2013 The main villain in the series. He is a childish scientist who comes up with a variety of inventions and dislikes the PJ Masks, who always foil his plans. He also dislikes the other villains such as Luna Girl and Night Ninja, who he trapped in \"Romeo's Disguise\", although they did team up in \"PJ Masks vs. Bad Guys United.\" He also dislikes it when his servants disobey him. His favorite inventions (as said in \"Owlette's New Move\") are Robot, his Laboggan (which is his mobile lab, with skis in place of [[Continuous track|Caterpillar]] tracks), Super Train, and Radical Romeo Remote. From \"Blame it on the Train, Owlette\" to \"The Prank Wheelz\", he originally controlled a mobile Lab on land, but now controls his flying Sky Factory starting in \"Villain of the Sky\". He always tries to take over the world and defeat the PJs but regularly fails. Once, though, he took over the city, turning it into Romeo-aplolis in \"Gekko and the Mayhem at the Museum\". He did once help the PJ Masks in \"The PJ Masks Save Christmas.\" when he realised how much Robot cares for him despite the rotten things he has done. Even though he may be evil, Robot mentions that there is good in Romeo deep down.\n** Robots - Romeo's mechanical henchmen.\n*** Robot (voiced by Ron Pardo) \u2013 A large [[robot]], Romeo's personal servant and his buddy as Romeo mentions it in \" Catboy and Gekko's Robot Rampage.\". He has acted on his own,  when Romeo invented Robette and when he captured Armadylan, Despite Romeo replacing him, Robot shows that he still cares for his master and is always willing to help him. Robot's main weakness is water, as it causes him to short-circuit and be paralyzed. Whenever this happens he often says \"Robots hate water.\"\n*** Robette (actor unknown) \u2013 One of Romeo's inventions. She began to try to take over the world herself in \"Catboy and Gekko's Robot Rampage\". This was due to a loose screw caused by Owlette and was later resolved. During the episode, Romeo's original Robot became jealous of Robette, and ran away. This was also later resolved, and Romeo became friends with Robot again. Robette returned in the Season 2 episode \"PJ Robot\". In \"Armadylan and Robette Rule\", she ends up as Armadylan's sidekick but then went back to Romeo.\n*** Toolbox \u2013 A walking toolbox who works with Romeo, and in case of making inventions Toolbox carries Romeo's tools.\n*** Spy-Bot \u2013 A cubical bot that works for Romeo, who often used Spy-Bot to spy on the PJ Masks.\n*** Fly Bots \u2013 Small, flying robots which resemble PJ Robot before he reformed and regularly guard Romeo's Sky Factory.\n*** Naughty Bots - Naughty Bots are robots disguised as [[Gift| presents]], but they destroy everything related to [[Christmas|Christmas]] \u2013 like presents and Christmas decorations\n*** Robo-PJ Masks - As the robotic versions of the PJ Masks, they all have the same powers but with the addition of Laser Eyes which stops the enemies from moving.\n* Luna Girl (a.k.a. Luna) (voiced by Brianna Daguanno) \u2013 The second villain in the series who is also the first villainess. She is an [[Extraterrestrial life|alien]] girl who lives on the [[Moon]] in her Lunar Fortress with her little sister Motsuki and their moths, but in \"Best Friends Forever\", it is revealed that her Luna Magnet powers give her the power to breathe in space. Her main weapons are her Luna Magnet and Luna Board that she uses as a mode of transportation. However, she also had a lot of other weapons; this once included a giant Moon-Ball, which could steal objects and swallow her enemies and the small Moon Ball, which turns the person who touches it to servants. She teamed with PJ Masks while defeating Romeo in some episodes when it came to him threatening the Moon or using her stolen lunar crystal. Starting in Season 3, she is persistently nicknamed Luna, rather than being called by her full name. In \"Gekko Saves Christmas\", she is shown to develop a crush on Gekko and at the end, they team up to put Christmas right. In \u201cBest Friends Forever\u201d at the end of the episode (like Gekko Saves Christmas), and she also joins the PJ Masks victory! She also helps the PJ Masks in \u201cPJ Party Crasher\u201d when Motsuki try to ruin Owlette\u2019s pajama party and was even invited to her slumber party. Also, she and Romeo team up in \u201cPJ Masks VS Bad Guy United\u201d when Romeo allied with Night Ninja and Luna Girl to defeat the PJs forever and in \u201cPJ Comet\u201d when Romeo and Luna Girl work together to Trap the PJ Masks in a fake comet and try to build a Villain HQ! But although being a villain towards the PJ Masks, Luna Girl is shown to have a good side sometimes that some fans believe that she will turn good and ally with them more often.\n** Moths \u2013 A swarm of [[Moth|moths]] who work for Luna.  They also have the ability to fly on the moon.\n*** Motsuki (voiced by Hattie Kragten) \u2013 The first moth to go to the moon with Luna Girl and receive her own powers from her mistress in \"Moon Madness\". Previously nicknamed \"Moth\" and \"Hench-Moth\" by Catboy, Luna was originally going to call her either \"Mothena\" or \"Motherella\", but eventually stuck with \"Motsuki\". Motsuki has the power to sense someone in the Lunar Fortress and can also shoot moon beams from her antennas to trap her victims in a purple bubble. Thanks to the PJ Masks' bad vibes, she later turns into a more anthropomorphic and more powerful, moth-like insectoid girl after hatching from a strange crystal on the moon in \"Moth on the Moon\", as intended by Luna. Following her transformation, she is given the power of speech and has a smaller crystal on her chest that has the same purpose as Luna's Luna Magnet. Despite this, she also becomes much less loyal to Luna, who now sees her as a younger sister, and enjoys annoying her, but she still loves her either way. She also has the tendency to occasionally make high-pitched squeaking noises really often. In \"Minding Motsuki\", she appears to be more loyal towards Gekko than towards Luna, as she treats her like a baby while he treats her like she's a guest.\n* Night Ninja (voiced by Trek Buccino in Season 1, Devan Cohen in the short films and Season 2-\"Do the Gekko\" and Jacob Soley in \"Armadylan, Action Hero\"-present) \u2013 Night Ninja, as his name suggests, is a [[ninja]] who rarely gets into battle as he makes his Ninjalinos do all his work and is the third villain of the series. He and Romeo have occasionally teamed up: in \"Catboy and the Shrinker\", when Romeo needed someone to help operate his shrink ray; and in \"Wacky Floats\" where they stole the parade floats and plotted to transform them into Robot Floats. In both episodes, they always argued and disagreed with each other. He did help the PJs twice in \"Wolfy Mountain\" and in \u201cWerejalinos\u201d to stop the Wolfies, from taking control of the Mystery Mountain and in \"The  Disappearing Ninjas\" when Romeo stole his Ninjalinos and invade Mystery Mountain. His main weapon is Sticky Splat which he normally uses to trap his opponents, he also uses [[Smoke bomb|smoke bombs]] to teleport to place to another.\n* Ninjalinos (actors unknown) \u2013 The minions of Night Ninja. They are small purple ninjas that talk in their own, unintelligible language (though Night Ninja does seem to understand them). Their numbers increased from episode to episode, from as few as three to well over a dozen. They sometimes get along well with the PJ Masks, much to their boss' chagrin.\n** Marvin (actor unknown) \u2013 A Ninjalino who was named. He appeared in \"Wolfy Mountain\" and \"Werejalinos\"\n** Daisy (actor unknown) \u2013 A female Ninjalino who was named. She appeared in \"The Disappearing Ninjas\".\n* The Wolfy Kids (usually referred to as \"the Wolfies\") \u2013 A trio of [[werewolf]] siblings who like to cause mischief. They ride in their car they call the \"Wolf Wheelz\". They may have been inspired by Les Mascrapules (lit. the Masked Scoundrels), a trio of villain kids from the books who also like to mess around and do as they please! They and The PJ Masks team up to defeat Luna Girl in two episode. They are show in \"Arma-Leader\" to be good after all since they help the PJs to rescue Armadylan and also another teaming with the PJs in \u201cWolfy Powers\u201d when Romeo stole the PJ Masks's powers and the Wolfies help them to retrieve their PJ powers.\n** Rip (voiced by Shechinah Mpumlwana) \u2013 The female member and leader of the Wolfy Kids who is the second villainess in the series. She has dark magenta hair with light tips and bone-shaped hair clips.\n** Howler (voiced by Kaden Stephen) \u2013 A male member of the Wolfy Kids, with white streak in his black hair.\n** Kevin (voiced by Ethan Pugiotto) \u2013 A male and younger member of the Wolfy Kids, always nicer than his brother and sister. He is a friend of Gekko.\n***Wolf Wheelz \u2013 The car of the Wolfy Kids. Originally three scooters used by the humanoid wolves, it transformed into a car in \"The Moon Prix\" as a result of being exposed to moon energy. In \"Where's the Wolf Wheelz?\", it is revealed that the car has a mind of its own.\n* Night [[Panthera|Panther]] (voiced by Jacob Ursomarzo) \u2013 The evil version of Catboy who appeared in \"Gekko and the Opposite Ray\". He also has the same powers like Catboy, like his Super Cat Stripes, only he calls it Night Panther Stripes.\n* Dark [[Owl]] (voiced by Addison Holley) \u2013 The evil version of Owlette who appeared in \"Gekko and the Opposite Ray\". Like Night Panther, she has the same powers as her couterpart, like Dark Owl Feathers which are like Owlette's Owl Feathers.\n* Octobella (voiced by Simon Pirso) \u2013 Another upcoming character for season 4 who, as her name suggests, will be an [[octopus]]-themed villain, as well as the series' third villainess (yet despite being set to debut in season 4, one of her tentacles can be seen in the end of \"Gekko Everywhere\"). She was leaked in a now-removed storyboard video for an upcoming episode for season 4, titled \"Octobella's Garden\". Since the storyboard video for said episode is no longer available for viewing online, it was unknown on what Octobella will look like until \"Gekko Everywhere\", when one of her tentacles was seen grabbing the Teleporting Crystal; it was light green with a hint of orange at the base. Besides that, her other half is currently unseen, so your best bet is to wait until \"Octobella's Garden\" (or whatever episode she'll first fully appear in) comes out. One other thing about her that we do know, however, is that she has a beautiful singing voice which is enough to attract Armadylan and make him fall in love with her.\n** Percival \u2013 Octobella's [[hermit crab]] sidekick.\n\n===Recurring===\n* Cameron (voiced by Tristan Samuel in Season 1, Jonah Wineberg in Season 2, Tyler Nathan in Season 3-present) \u2013 A boy in the same class as PJ Masks when they attend school during the day as civilians. He once scared Amaya with a T-Rex cutout the same way Connor did earlier in \"Owlette's Terrible Pterodactyl Trouble\", but Connor learned his lesson and tells Cameron not to do it. In \"Catboy's Cuddly\", he was revealed to have a sister (named Marie as of \"PJ Party Crasher\"), who attends the same school.\n* Teacher (voiced by [[Robert Tinkler|Rob Tinkler]]) \u2013 An unnamed adult male who teaches Connor, Greg, and Amaya's class. When things disappear, he thinks it's strange.\n* Jayden Houston \u2013 A popular singer, known for his golden microphone. It was stolen by Luna Girl in \"Catboy's Tricky Ticket\", but was later recovered by the PJ Masks.\n* Master Fang (actor unknown) \u2013 The protagonist of his own comic book and TV series. Greg and Connor generally looked up to him, but Amaya doesn't seem to care about him much. He is known for his signature sword that was stolen by Night Ninja in \"Catboy and Master Fang's Sword\".\n** Kick McGee \u2013 Master Fang's unseen sidekick. His persona is often used during missions.\n* Flossy Flash \u2013 A female comic book superhero, looked up to by Owlette and Armadylan. Owlette prefers her over Master Fang and Kick McGee, who are favored by Catboy and Gekko.\n* The Announcer (voiced by Ron Pardo) \u2013 A male voice that is heard in every episode as the day becomes night. He is never seen, but is known for saying his signature introduction sequence \"Night in the city, and a brave band of heroes is ready to face fiendish villains to stop them messing with your day.\" As the kids turn into their superhero forms, the announcer states who turns into who.\n*Marie (voice actor unknown) - Marie is Cameron's sister.  Like Cameron, Marie has green eyes and brown hair. She is one of Amaya's friends. Her name was revealed in, \u201cPJ Party Crasher\u201d.\n*Jenny (voice actor unknown) - Jenny is one of Amaya's friends.\n*Unknown Monkey - An upcoming character in Season 4.  First seen at the New York Toy Fair 2020 as an action figure. They don't have a name or gender yet, but it might be the confirmed third new character for the season.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of PJ Masks episodes}}\n{{:List of PJ Masks episodes}}\n\n==Production==\n''PJ Masks'' is a British/French coproduction by [[Entertainment One]], Frog Box, and [[TeamTO]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/festivals/annecy-teamto-re-ups-pj-masks-skylanders-1201798571/|title=Annecy: TeamTO Re-Ups on 'PJ Masks,' 'Skylanders' (EXCLUSIVE)|work=Variety|author1=John Hopewell|author2=Emilio Mayorga|date=June 18, 2016|access-date=May 6, 2018}}</ref> The series was renewed for a second season consisting of 52 11-minute segments in June 2016;<ref name=\"THR\">{{cite web |author=Georg Szalai |date=June 15, 2016 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-juniors-pj-masks-get-903016 |title=Disney Junior's 'PJ Masks' to Get Second Season |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=May 6, 2018}}</ref> it premiered on 15 January 2018. The series was renewed for a third season on 22 January 2018;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kidscreen.com/2018/01/22/pj-masks-flies-into-production-on-season-three/|title=PJ Masks flies into production on season three|author=Lauren Malyk|date=January 22, 2018|website=Kidscreen|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref> originally meant to premier in June 2019, it instead premiered on 19 April that same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Disney-Channel-to-Air-Third-Season-of-PJ-MASKS-on-April-19-20190326|title=Disney Channel to Air Third Season of PJ MASKS on April 19|work=Broadway World|date=March 26, 2019|accessdate=March 28, 2019}}</ref> A fourth season was announced to air in spring 2020. The fifth season is in production as of 28 January 2020 and will be released in spring 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/eone-soars-into-production-of-pj-masks-season-5/|title=eOne Soars Into Production of \u2018PJ Masks\u2019 Season 5|work=Animation Magazine|date=January 28, 2020|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|France|United Kingdom|Television|Disney}}\n*{{Official website|www.pjmasks.com}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=4148744}}\n*{{Thetvdb|id=300921}}\n*{{website|http://disneyjunior.disney.com/pj-masks|''PJ Masks''}} on [[Disney Junior]]\n*{{website|http://eonefamily.com/our-brands/pj-masks|''PJ Masks''}} on [[Entertainment One]]\n*{{website|http://www.frogbox.fr/en/our-productions-pjmasks.html|''PJ Masks''}} on Frog Box\n*{{website|http://www.teamto.com/en/les-productions/les-productions-executives/pyjamasques|''PJ Masks''}} on [[TeamTO]]\n\n{{Disney Junior}}\n{{Disney Channel co-productions}}\n\n[[Category:PJ Masks| ]]\n[[Category:2010s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:2010s French animated television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:2020s French animated television series]]\n[[Category:2015 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2015 French television series debuts]]\n[[Category:British children's animated action television series]]\n[[Category:British children's animated science fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:British children's animated superhero television series]]\n[[Category:British computer-animated television series]]\n[[Category:French children's animated action television series]]\n[[Category:French children's animated science fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:French children's animated superhero television series]]\n[[Category:French computer-animated television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Disney Junior shows]]\n[[Category:Fictional French people]]\n[[Category:British television programmes based on children's books]]\n[[Category:Television series by Entertainment One]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about robots]]\n", "text_old": "{{use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{use American English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = PJ Masks\n| image                    = PJ-Masks-logo-2.png\n| caption                  = Current logo of the series\n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Action film|Action]]\n*[[Superhero film|Superhero]]\n*[[Science fiction]]\n*[[Drama]]\n}}\n| creator                  = Romuald Racioppo\n| based_on                 = {{based on|''[[Les Pyjamasques]]''|Romuald Racioppo}}\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n*Christian De Vita\n*Wilson Dos Santos\n*Florante Mari Villareal\n*Chad V. Vidanes\n}}\n| voices                   = {{Plainlist|\n*Roman Lutterotti\n*[[Addison Holley]]\n*[[Claire Corlett]]\n*Simon Pirso\n*Jacob Soley\n*Brianna Daguanno\n}}\n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = {{Plainlist|\n*Eric Renwart\n*[[David Freedman (screenwriter)|David Freedman]]\n}}\n| composer                 = Fabrice Aboulker<br />Jean-Francois Berger\n| country                  = {{Plainlist|\n*France\n*United Kingdom\n}}\n| language                 = {{Plainlist|\n*French\n*English\n}}\n| num_seasons              = 5<!-- season the last aired episode belongs to -->\n| num_episodes             = 66<!-- number released or aired --> (and 41 shorts)\n| list_episodes            = List of PJ Masks episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n*Olivier Dumont\n*Laura Clunie\n*Beth Gardiner\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n*Guillaume Hellouin\n*Corinne Kouper\n}}\n| runtime                  = 24 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Entertainment One]]\n*Frog Box Productions\n*[[TeamTO]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teamto.com/en/les-productions/les-productions-executives/pyjamasques|title=PJmasks|work=[[TeamTO]]|accessdate=December 1, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402113704/http://www.teamto.com/en/les-productions/les-productions-executives/pyjamasques|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref> (Season 2-present)\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Entertainment One]]\n| network                  = [[France 5]] (France)<br>[[Disney Junior]]\n| picture_format           = [[HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n| audio_format             = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2015|9|18}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| website                  = http://pjmasks.com\n| production_website       = \n}}\n'''''PJ Masks''''' (French: Pyjamasques) is a French-British [[Computer animated|CGI-animated]] [[Superhero fiction|superhero]] [[children's television series]] produced by Frog Box, [[Entertainment One|Entertainment One UK Limited]], [[TeamTO]], with the participation of [[France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions]] and [[Disney Junior]]. The series is based on the ''[[Les Pyjamasques]]'' book series by Romuald Racioppo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awn.com/news/pj-masks-sees-strong-us-debut|title=\u2018PJ Masks\u2019 Sees Strong U.S. Debut|author=Jennifer Wolfe|work=[[Animation World Network]]|date=October 2, 2015|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref> [[Disney Channels Worldwide]]'s Disney Junior channels broadcast ''PJ Masks'' worldwide, while [[France 5]] airs the series in its original home country of [[France]]; it also airs on [[Tiny Pop]] in the [[United Kingdom|UK]], [[ABC Kids (Australia)|ABC Kids]] in [[Australia]], [[Rai YoYo|RAI YoYo]] in [[Italy]], [[TV Cultura]] in [[Brazil]], and [[Televisa]] in [[Mexico]]. The series debuted on Disney Junior in the [[United States]] on 18 September 2015, on France 5 on 18 December 2015, and on [[Disney Junior (Canadian TV channel)|Disney Junior]] in [[Canada]] on 7 February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/programming/disney-channel-disney-junior-debut-pj-masks-sept-18/143830|title=Disney Channel, Disney Junior to Debut \u2018PJ Masks\u2019 Sept. 18|author=Luke McCord|work=Broadcasting & Cable|date=September 2, 2015|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref> In June 2016, a second season, consisting of another 52 11-minute segments, was announced;<ref name=\"THR\" /> it began airing on 15 January 2017. On 19 April 2019, the first episode of the third season was aired. The start of the fourth season was announced to air in April or May 2020.\n\nThe first two seasons of the show became available to stream on [[Disney+]] on its launch, November 12, 2019, with seasons 3, 4 and 5 being available after their finales have aired.\n\nOn 5 May 2019, [[Hasbro]] acquired Entertainment One for a $3.8 billion deal,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/12/30/hasbro-entertainment-one-eone-peppa-pig-pj-masks-ricky-zoom-movies-television/|title=Hasbro's Toy Box Is Bigger Than Ever With $3.8 Billion Entertainment One Takeover|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> making the series under the ownership of [[Hasbro]].\n\n==Premise==\nAmaya, Greg, and Connor become the [[fictional character|fictional]] superhero team PJ Masks when night falls in order to fight enemies and rivals such as Romeo, Luna Girl, Night Ninja, and Motsuki, The Wolfy Kids and Octobella to keep them from ruining people's day. Amaya becomes Owlette (an [[owl]]), Greg becomes Gekko (a [[lizard]]), and Connor becomes Catboy (a [[cat]]).\n\n==Characters==\n===PJ Masks===\n'''PJ Masks''' (known as \"PJs\" for short) is the titular superhero team that fights crime at night to keep it from ruining people's days. Their catchphrase when planning to go fight their enemies is \"PJ Masks, we're on our way. Into the night, to save the day!\" Their base is hidden in a totem-like structure in the park, called their \"HQ\", which also houses a crystal that grants them their abilities. When the villains are defeated, their victory catchphrase is \"PJ Masks, all shout hooray, 'cause in the night, we saved the day!\" Among its members and allies are:\n\n====Members====\n* Connor / Catboy (voiced by [[Jacob Ewaniuk]] in Season 1, Jacob Ursomarzo in Season 2-\"Best Friends Forever\", and Roman Lutterotti in \"Meet An Yu\"-present) \u2013 Connor is a blue-eyed boy with brown hair. When he transforms, he wears a blue [[cat]] costume with cat ears and a thin feline tail.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Catboy and the Shrinker|series=PJ Masks|quote=I'm not that little, and I can still be your leader.}}</ref> He has super-hearing using Cat Ears, can leap high and far using Super Cat Jump (or \"Super Cat Leap\"), and sprints fast using Super Cat Speed,<ref name=ep2>{{cite episode|series=PJ Masks|number=2}}</ref> or just Super Speed.<ref name=SuperMS>{{cite episode|title=Owlette and the Moonball|series=PJ Masks|minutes=21|quote=We need to play as a team. Gekko, use your Super Muscles, Catboy, use your Super Speed, and I'll use my Owl Wing Wind!}}</ref> Starting in season 2, he also has Super Cat Stripes. When on a mission, he sometimes likes to narrate his actions. His main flaws are his [[impulsiveness]] and his need to control, flaws that can be exploited by the team's opponents. He is the only member of the team that [[Aquaphobia|hates water]]. His vehicle is the Cat Car, which is located in the middle segment of the PJ Masks' tower. It can launch blue hairballs at any obstacle. His bedroom is on the second floor of a blue-roofed blue-doored house next to Amaya's house. Unlike Amaya and Greg, Connor is the only one without a pet.\n** Kitten Boy (voiced by Jacob Ursomarzo in \"Terrible Two-Some\", Roman Lutterotti in \"Big Sister Motsuki\") \u2013 The baby-fied version of Catboy who appeared in \"Terrible Two-Some\". Unlike Chicklette, he acts like a [[kitten]]. Whenever he uses his super cat speed, he exclaims \u201cSuper Cat Speed, and whoosh!\u201d He and Chicklette returned in \"Big Sister Motsuki\".\n* Amaya / Owlette (voiced by [[Addison Holley]]) \u2013 Amaya is a brown-eyed girl who wears red glasses, as well as PJ Masks' only female member besides An Yu. She has dark brown hair with a pink, wing-shaped hair clip. When she transforms, she wears a red [[owl]] costume with a dark red [[facial disc]] and a cape made of artificial feathers (dubbed her \"Super Owl Wings\"), which helps her fly. She also loses her glasses and presumably wears contact lenses. Her eyes also become an intense, blood-red color that matches her suit. She has Owl Eyes that let her see things that are far away up close, and she also has Super Owl Wing Wind, or just Owl Wing Wind (She also occasionally has super strength). Starting in season 2, she also has Super Owl Feathers, which sometimes form a Super Feather Shield. Despite being a member of PJ Masks, as well as being as adorable and likable as her teammates, she is also rude and unlikable at times (most notably in \"Glowy Moths\", where she even teamed up with Luna to get revenge on Romeo). While she doesn't mind water as Amaya, as seen in \"Catboy's Cloudy Crisis\", she is rarely soaked as Owlette. But when she is, the feathers on her suit get really soggy.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Catboy's Two Wheeled Wonder|series=PJ Masks|quote=I'm okay. But he got all my feathers wet.}}</ref> During PJ Masks Takeover Weekend on Disney Junior, she is revealed to also be the smartest member of the team. Her vehicle is the Owl-Glider, which can also do a \"Super Owl Wing Wind\". It is located in the top segment of the PJ Masks' tower. Her bedroom is on the third floor of a red-roofed red-doored home with a walled-in yard between Connor and Greg's houses. Amaya owns a bird named Birdie. Despite the fact that she is Connor's best friend, she flirts with him for convincing him to give the extra ticket to her (much to Greg/Gekko's chagrin) in \"Catboy's Tricky Ticket\". Owlette is male in the books.\n** Chicklette (also voiced by Addison Holley) \u2013 The baby-fied version of Owlette who appeared in \"Terrible Two-Some\". Whenever she uses her super owl wing wind, she exclaims \u201cSuper Owly Wingy-Wind!\u201d She and Kitten Boy returned in \"Big Sister Motsuki\".\n* Greg / Gekko (voiced by [[Kyle Harrison Breitkopf]] in Season 1-Season 3 and the short films and [[Claire Corlett]] in \"HQ Tour\" and Season 4-present) \u2013 Greg is a green-eyed, blonde-haired boy. When he transforms, he wears a green [[lizard]] costume with a thick reptilian tail and fins on top of his head. His powers are: Super Gekko Camouflage to go invisible or blend into the environment around him, Super Gekko Muscles (aka Super Muscles<ref name=SuperMS/>) to lift heavy things, like the HQ, Super Lizard Grip to climb walls or anchor himself to stop vehicles, and Super Lizard Water Run to walk on water.<ref name=ep2/> He has exhibited enough strength to lift a mobile laboratory (namely Romeo's) off the ground. Starting in season 2, he also has Super Lizard Shields, which can create shields. He is the only semi-aquatic member of the PJ Masks. His vehicle is the Gekko-Mobile, which is also a submersible vehicle that can travel underwater and can also ride up & over buildings via land on tank treads; it is slower than the Cat-Car. His vehicle is located in the bottom segment of the PJ Masks' tower. The vehicle has abilities similar to him, with a \"Gekko-Mobile Camouflage\" letting it blend in with surroundings. His bedroom is on the second floor of a green-roofed green-doored house next to Amaya's. Greg has a gecko named Lionel. In seasons 1\u20132, an ongoing joke about how he \"can't think of a rhyme\" was finished in \"Pirates Ahoy!\" when he sang with Owlette/Amaya, where they were singing about each other and he thought of a rhyme for the relationship of them both in that segment. It is hinted that he has a slim crush on Amaya/Owlette, but some fans believe that he has a crush on Luna Girl. He is also Connor's best friend and is treated like a little brother.\n** Baby Gekko (voiced by Kyle Harrison Breitkopf) \u2013 The baby-fied version of Gekko who appeared in \"Big Sister Motsuki\". Unlike the other baby PJs, he is the only one who never speaks by himself and usually only speaks in unison with the other babies. However, at one point, he did say \"Muscle Wuscles!\" when he used his Super Gekko Muscles.\n* PJ Robot (voiced by Juan Luis Bonilla) \u2013 A robot that Romeo created to infiltrate the PJ Masks HQ. However, PJ Robot decided to be a PJ Mask rather than a villain's sidekick. He joined the PJ Masks Team in Season 2. He spends most of his time inside HQ as mission control for the PJ Masks. He doesn't speak much, but when he does, it usually comes out as robotic gibberish that only the PJ Masks and Romeo can understand. He is the creator of the PJ Seeker.\n\n====Allies====\n* Teeny Weeny Ninjalino (actor unknown) \u2013 A tiny and cute ninja from \"Catboy and the Teeny Weeny Ninjalino\", who was supposed to spy on the PJ Masks but won Owlette and Gekko's affection. Catboy (who was too quick to judge him, but later became his friend after being unstuck from the Owl Glider by him) kept wanting to get rid of him, and convinced his teammates to do so as well. He returned in \"Race Up Mystery Mountain\", where he mostly interacted with Gekko. In \"A Teeny Weeny Problem\", Teeny turned on his master. But in \"The Disappearing Ninjas\" he returned to his master's side.\n** The Splat Monster (actor unknown) \u2013 The alternate form Teeny took in the episode of the same name, where he turned into a Splat Monster when he touched the transforming splat in the Mystery Mountain cave. The Teeny Weeny Ninjalino was restored to normal by An Yu. This form returned in \"A Teeny Weeny Problem\" and again in \"The Disappearing Ninjas.\"\n* Armadylan (voiced by Max Calinescu in Season 2-\"Armadylan Zen\", Christian Perri in \"Arma-Leader\"-present) \u2013 An [[armadillo]]-like boy who wants to be a hero, but his being inexperienced causes him to mess up. He first meets the PJ Masks in \"Meet Armadylan\" and became an official member of the PJ Masks team in the episode \"PJ Dylan\". Armadylan's powers are his Thunder Thump to shake the ground, super strength to lift any heavy objects, like Gekko, the Rolling Thunder to roll himself up into a ball to attack his opponents and he can also dig to go underneath the ground. He is mostly mistaken by Romeo and Night Ninja for an anteater and/or an aardvark instead of an armadillo. He has a crush on either Rip or Octobella.\n* Captain Smartypants (voiced by Carter Thorne) \u2013 A young scientist who is the good version of Romeo. He helps Gekko change his teammates back to normal before Robot changes him back to his usual, evil self in \"Gekko and the Opposite Ray\".\n* An Yu (voiced by Kari Wong) \u2013 A samurai girl who uses her bo staff as a weapon or to fly; it also turns into a magic flute. She also turned out to be the human form of the Dragon from the Dragon Gong, as hinted by the gold dragon head on her headdress. She first appears in her human form in the season 3 episode \"Meet An Yu\". An Yu was a loner{{snd}}she attempted to face Night Ninja (from the episode \"Meet An Yu\") alone without the PJ Masks{{snd}}but they helped her out anyway, and she has occasionally helped them out in return. An Yu's powers mostly work on Mystery Mountain, and she can't use her magic flute in the town either, as seen in \"A Teeny Weeny Problem\".\n*Lionel (actor unknown) \u2013 a small gekko who is the pet of Gekko, he normally appeared when the PJ Masks are transforming. He then had a major role in \"Lionel-saurs.\" when Romeo made him huge.\n*[[Santa Claus|Santa ]](voiced by [[Ron Pardo]]) - Santa is the jolly man who appeared in \"The PJ Masks Save Christmas.\" where he teamed up with the PJ Masks to stop Romeo from running [[Christmas]]. He appears with a long beard and was not as fat as the other adaptations of him.\n* Newton (actor unknown at the moment) \u2013 An upcoming character who is set to appear in season 4, and was first seen in a storyboard video for the season's 14th episode. He has star powers. He is likely to be the first hero to appear in both daytime and nighttime.\n\n===Villains===\n* Romeo (voiced by Alex Thorne in Season 1, Carter Thorne in the short films and Season 2-\"Owlette Slips Up\", Simon Pirso in \"Motsuki the Best\"-present) \u2013 The main villain in the series. He is a childish scientist who comes up with a variety of inventions and dislikes the PJ Masks, who always foil his plans. He also dislikes the other villains such as Luna Girl and Night Ninja, who he trapped in \"Romeo's Disguise\", although they did team up in \"PJ Masks vs. Bad Guys United.\" He also dislikes it when his servants disobey him. His favorite inventions (as said in \"Owlette's New Move\") are Robot, his Laboggan (which is his mobile lab, with skis in place of [[Continuous track|Caterpillar]] tracks), Super Train, and Radical Romeo Remote. From \"Blame it on the Train, Owlette\" to \"The Prank Wheelz\", he originally controlled a mobile Lab on land, but now controls his flying Sky Factory starting in \"Villain of the Sky\". He always tries to take over the world and defeat the PJs but regularly fails. Once, though, he took over the city, turning it into Romeo-aplolis in \"Gekko and the Mayhem at the Museum\". He did once help the PJ Masks in \"The PJ Masks Save Christmas.\" when he realised how much Robot cares for him despite the rotten things he has done. Even though he may be evil, Robot mentions that there is good in Romeo deep down.\n** Robots - Romeo's mechanical henchmen.\n*** Robot (voiced by Ron Pardo) \u2013 A large [[robot]], Romeo's personal servant and his buddy as Romeo mentions it in \" Catboy and Gekko's Robot Rampage.\". He has acted on his own,  when Romeo invented Robette and when he captured Armadylan, Despite Romeo replacing him, Robot shows that he still cares for his master and is always willing to help him. Robot's main weakness is water, as it causes him to short-circuit and be paralyzed. Whenever this happens he often says \"Robots hate water.\"\n*** Robette (actor unknown) \u2013 One of Romeo's inventions. She began to try to take over the world herself in \"Catboy and Gekko's Robot Rampage\". This was due to a loose screw caused by Owlette and was later resolved. During the episode, Romeo's original Robot became jealous of Robette, and ran away. This was also later resolved, and Romeo became friends with Robot again. Robette returned in the Season 2 episode \"PJ Robot\". In \"Armadylan and Robette Rule\", she ends up as Armadylan's sidekick but then went back to Romeo.\n*** Toolbox \u2013 A walking toolbox who works with Romeo, and in case of making inventions Toolbox carries Romeo's tools.\n*** Spy-Bot \u2013 A cubical bot that works for Romeo, who often used Spy-Bot to spy on the PJ Masks.\n*** Fly Bots \u2013 Small, flying robots which resemble PJ Robot before he reformed and regularly guard Romeo's Sky Factory.\n*** Naughty Bots - Naughty Bots are robots disguised as [[Gift| presents]], but they destroy everything related to [[Christmas|Christmas]] \u2013 like presents and Christmas decorations\n*** Robo-PJ Masks - As the robotic versions of the PJ Masks, they all have the same powers but with the addition of Laser Eyes which stops the enemies from moving.\n* Luna Girl (a.k.a. Luna) (voiced by Brianna Daguanno) \u2013 The second villain in the series who is also the first villainess. She is an [[Extraterrestrial life|alien]] girl who lives on the [[Moon]] in her Lunar Fortress with her little sister Motsuki and their moths, but in \"Best Friends Forever\", it is revealed that her Luna Magnet powers give her the power to breathe in space. Her main weapons are her Luna Magnet and Luna Board that she uses as a mode of transportation. However, she also had a lot of other weapons; this once included a giant Moon-Ball, which could steal objects and swallow her enemies and the small Moon Ball, which turns the person who touches it to servants. She teamed with PJ Masks while defeating Romeo in some episodes when it came to him threatening the Moon or using her stolen lunar crystal. Starting in Season 3, she is persistently nicknamed Luna, rather than being called by her full name. In \"Gekko Saves Christmas\", she is shown to develop a crush on Gekko and at the end, they team up to put Christmas right. In \u201cBest Friends Forever\u201d at the end of the episode (like Gekko Saves Christmas), and she also joins the PJ Masks victory! She also helps the PJ Masks in \u201cPJ Party Crasher\u201d when Motsuki try to ruin Owlette\u2019s pajama party and was even invited to her slumber party. Also, she and Romeo team up in \u201cPJ Masks VS Bad Guy United\u201d when Romeo allied with Night Ninja and Luna Girl to defeat the PJs forever and in \u201cPJ Comet\u201d when Romeo and Luna Girl work together to Trap the PJ Masks in a fake comet and try to build a Villain HQ! But although being a villain towards the PJ Masks, Luna Girl is shown to have a good side sometimes that some fans believe that she will turn good and ally with them more often.\n** Moths \u2013 A swarm of [[Moth|moths]] who work for Luna.  They also have the ability to fly on the moon.\n*** Motsuki (voiced by Hattie Kragten) \u2013 The first moth to go to the moon with Luna Girl and receive her own powers from her mistress in \"Moon Madness\". Previously nicknamed \"Moth\" and \"Hench-Moth\" by Catboy, Luna was originally going to call her either \"Mothena\" or \"Motherella\", but eventually stuck with \"Motsuki\". Motsuki has the power to sense someone in the Lunar Fortress and can also shoot moon beams from her antennas to trap her victims in a purple bubble. Thanks to the PJ Masks' bad vibes, she later turns into a more anthropomorphic and more powerful, moth-like insectoid girl after hatching from a strange crystal on the moon in \"Moth on the Moon\", as intended by Luna. Following her transformation, she is given the power of speech and has a smaller crystal on her chest that has the same purpose as Luna's Luna Magnet. Despite this, she also becomes much less loyal to Luna, who now sees her as a younger sister, and enjoys annoying her, but she still loves her either way. She also has the tendency to occasionally make high-pitched squeaking noises really often. In \"Minding Motsuki\", she appears to be more loyal towards Gekko than towards Luna, as she treats her like a baby while he treats her like she's a guest.\n* Night Ninja (voiced by Trek Buccino in Season 1, Devan Cohen in the short films and Season 2-\"Do the Gekko\" and Jacob Soley in \"Armadylan, Action Hero\"-present) \u2013 Night Ninja, as his name suggests, is a [[ninja]] who rarely gets into battle as he makes his Ninjalinos do all his work and is the third villain of the series. He and Romeo have occasionally teamed up: in \"Catboy and the Shrinker\", when Romeo needed someone to help operate his shrink ray; and in \"Wacky Floats\" where they stole the parade floats and plotted to transform them into Robot Floats. In both episodes, they always argued and disagreed with each other. He did help the PJs twice in \"Wolfy Mountain\" and in \u201cWerejalinos\u201d to stop the Wolfies, from taking control of the Mystery Mountain and in \"The  Disappearing Ninjas\" when Romeo stole his Ninjalinos and invade Mystery Mountain. His main weapon is Sticky Splat which he normally uses to trap his opponents, he also uses [[Smoke bomb|smoke bombs]] to teleport to place to another.\n* Ninjalinos (actors unknown) \u2013 The minions of Night Ninja. They are small purple ninjas that talk in their own, unintelligible language (though Night Ninja does seem to understand them). Their numbers increased from episode to episode, from as few as three to well over a dozen. They sometimes get along well with the PJ Masks, much to their boss' chagrin.\n** Marvin (actor unknown) \u2013 A Ninjalino who was named. He appeared in \"Wolfy Mountain\" and \"Werejalinos\"\n** Daisy (actor unknown) \u2013 A female Ninjalino who was named. She appeared in \"The Disappearing Ninjas\".\n* The Wolfy Kids (usually referred to as \"the Wolfies\") \u2013 A trio of [[werewolf]] siblings who like to cause mischief. They ride in their car they call the \"Wolf Wheelz\". They may have been inspired by Les Mascrapules (lit. the Masked Scoundrels), a trio of villain kids from the books who also like to mess around and do as they please! They and The PJ Masks team up to defeat Luna Girl in two episode. They are show in \"Arma-Leader\" to be good after all since they help the PJs to rescue Armadylan and also another teaming with the PJs in \u201cWolfy Powers\u201d when Romeo stole the PJ Masks's powers and the Wolfies help them to retrieve their PJ powers.\n** Rip (voiced by Shechinah Mpumlwana) \u2013 The female member and leader of the Wolfy Kids who is the second villainess in the series. She has dark magenta hair with light tips and bone-shaped hair clips.\n** Howler (voiced by Kaden Stephen) \u2013 A male member of the Wolfy Kids, with white streak in his black hair.\n** Kevin (voiced by Ethan Pugiotto) \u2013 A male and younger member of the Wolfy Kids, always nicer than his brother and sister. He is a friend of Gekko.\n***Wolf Wheelz \u2013 The car of the Wolfy Kids. Originally three scooters used by the humanoid wolves, it transformed into a car in \"The Moon Prix\" as a result of being exposed to moon energy. In \"Where's the Wolf Wheelz?\", it is revealed that the car has a mind of its own.\n* Night [[Panthera|Panther]] (voiced by Jacob Ursomarzo) \u2013 The evil version of Catboy who appeared in \"Gekko and the Opposite Ray\". He also has the same powers like Catboy, like his Super Cat Stripes, only he calls it Night Panther Stripes.\n* Dark [[Owl]] (voiced by Addison Holley) \u2013 The evil version of Owlette who appeared in \"Gekko and the Opposite Ray\". Like Night Panther, she has the same powers as her couterpart, like Dark Owl Feathers which are like Owlette's Owl Feathers.\n* Octobella (voiced by Simon Pirso) \u2013 Another upcoming character for season 4 who, as her name suggests, will be an [[octopus]]-themed villain, as well as the series' third villainess (yet despite being set to debut in season 4, one of her tentacles can be seen in the end of \"Gekko Everywhere\"). She was leaked in a now-removed storyboard video for an upcoming episode for season 4, titled \"Octobella's Garden\". Since the storyboard video for said episode is no longer available for viewing online, it was unknown on what Octobella will look like until \"Gekko Everywhere\", when one of her tentacles was seen grabbing the Teleporting Crystal; it was light green with a hint of orange at the base. Besides that, her other half is currently unseen, so your best bet is to wait until \"Octobella's Garden\" (or whatever episode she'll first fully appear in) comes out. One other thing about her that we do know, however, is that she has a beautiful singing voice which is enough to attract Armadylan and make him fall in love with her.\n** Percival \u2013 Octobella's [[hermit crab]] sidekick.\n\n===Recurring===\n* Cameron (voiced by Tristan Samuel in Season 1, Jonah Wineberg in Season 2, Tyler Nathan in Season 3-present) \u2013 A boy in the same class as PJ Masks when they attend school during the day as civilians. He once scared Amaya with a T-Rex cutout the same way Connor did earlier in \"Owlette's Terrible Pterodactyl Trouble\", but Connor learned his lesson and tells Cameron not to do it. In \"Catboy's Cuddly\", he was revealed to have a sister (named Marie as of \"PJ Party Crasher\"), who attends the same school.\n* Teacher (voiced by [[Robert Tinkler|Rob Tinkler]]) \u2013 An unnamed adult male who teaches Connor, Greg, and Amaya's class. When things disappear, he thinks it's strange.\n* Jayden Houston \u2013 A popular singer, known for his golden microphone. It was stolen by Luna Girl in \"Catboy's Tricky Ticket\", but was later recovered by the PJ Masks.\n* Master Fang (actor unknown) \u2013 The protagonist of his own comic book and TV series. Greg and Connor generally looked up to him, but Amaya doesn't seem to care about him much. He is known for his signature sword that was stolen by Night Ninja in \"Catboy and Master Fang's Sword\".\n** Kick McGee \u2013 Master Fang's unseen sidekick. His persona is often used during missions.\n* Flossy Flash \u2013 A female comic book superhero, looked up to by Owlette and Armadylan. Owlette prefers her over Master Fang and Kick McGee, who are favored by Catboy and Gekko.\n* The Announcer (voiced by Ron Pardo) \u2013 A male voice that is heard in every episode as the day becomes night. He is never seen, but is known for saying his signature introduction sequence \"Night in the city, and a brave band of heroes is ready to face fiendish villains to stop them messing with your day.\" As the kids turn into their superhero forms, the announcer states who turns into who.\n*Marie (voice actor unknown) - Marie is Cameron's sister.  Like Cameron, Marie has green eyes and brown hair. She is one of Amaya's friends. Her name was revealed in, \u201cPJ Party Crasher\u201d.\n*Jenny (voice actor unknown) - Jenny is one of Amaya's friends.\n*Unknown Monkey - An upcoming character in Season 4.  First seen at the New York Toy Fair 2020 as an action figure. They don't have a name or gender yet, but it might be the confirmed third new character for the season.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of PJ Masks episodes}}\n{{:List of PJ Masks episodes}}\n\n==Production==\n''PJ Masks'' is a British/French coproduction by [[Entertainment One]], Frog Box, and [[TeamTO]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/festivals/annecy-teamto-re-ups-pj-masks-skylanders-1201798571/|title=Annecy: TeamTO Re-Ups on 'PJ Masks,' 'Skylanders' (EXCLUSIVE)|work=Variety|author1=John Hopewell|author2=Emilio Mayorga|date=June 18, 2016|access-date=May 6, 2018}}</ref> The series was renewed for a second season consisting of 52 11-minute segments in June 2016;<ref name=\"THR\">{{cite web |author=Georg Szalai |date=June 15, 2016 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-juniors-pj-masks-get-903016 |title=Disney Junior's 'PJ Masks' to Get Second Season |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=May 6, 2018}}</ref> it premiered on 15 January 2018. The series was renewed for a third season on 22 January 2018;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kidscreen.com/2018/01/22/pj-masks-flies-into-production-on-season-three/|title=PJ Masks flies into production on season three|author=Lauren Malyk|date=January 22, 2018|website=Kidscreen|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref> originally meant to premier in June 2019, it instead premiered on 19 April that same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Disney-Channel-to-Air-Third-Season-of-PJ-MASKS-on-April-19-20190326|title=Disney Channel to Air Third Season of PJ MASKS on April 19|work=Broadway World|date=March 26, 2019|accessdate=March 28, 2019}}</ref> A fourth season was announced to air in spring 2020. The fifth season is in production as of 28 January 2020 and will be released in spring 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/eone-soars-into-production-of-pj-masks-season-5/|title=eOne Soars Into Production of \u2018PJ Masks\u2019 Season 5|work=Animation Magazine|date=January 28, 2020|accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|France|United Kingdom|Television|Disney}}\n*{{Official website|www.pjmasks.com}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=4148744}}\n*{{Thetvdb|id=300921}}\n*{{website|http://disneyjunior.disney.com/pj-masks|''PJ Masks''}} on [[Disney Junior]]\n*{{website|http://eonefamily.com/our-brands/pj-masks|''PJ Masks''}} on [[Entertainment One]]\n*{{website|http://www.frogbox.fr/en/our-productions-pjmasks.html|''PJ Masks''}} on Frog Box\n*{{website|http://www.teamto.com/en/les-productions/les-productions-executives/pyjamasques|''PJ Masks''}} on [[TeamTO]]\n\n{{Disney Junior}}\n{{Disney Channel co-productions}}\n\n[[Category:PJ Masks| ]]\n[[Category:2010s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:2010s French animated television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:2020s French animated television series]]\n[[Category:2015 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2015 French television series debuts]]\n[[Category:British children's animated action television series]]\n[[Category:British children's animated science fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:British children's animated superhero television series]]\n[[Category:British computer-animated television series]]\n[[Category:French children's animated action television series]]\n[[Category:French children's animated science fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:French children's animated superhero television series]]\n[[Category:French computer-animated television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Disney Junior shows]]\n[[Category:Fictional French people]]\n[[Category:British television programmes based on children's books]]\n[[Category:Television series by Entertainment One]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about robots]]\n", "name_user": "SafariKid2", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PJ_Masks"}
{"title_page": "12 Monkeys (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|2015 American television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = 12 Monkeys\n| image                    = 12 Monkeys Intertitle.png\n| caption                  = <!-- don't say \"title card\", \"intertitle\" or similar, it's unnecessary and stating the obvious -->\n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Science fiction]]\n* [[Mystery fiction|Mystery]]\n* [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]}}\n| based_on                 = {{Based on|''[[La Jet\u00e9e]]''|[[Chris Marker]]}}<br />{{Based on|''[[12 Monkeys]]''|[[David Peoples]]<br />[[Janet Peoples]]}}\n| developer                = Terry Matalas<br />Travis Fickett\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Aaron Stanford]]\n* [[Amanda Schull]]\n* [[Kirk Acevedo]]\n* [[Noah Bean]]\n* [[Todd Stashwick]]\n* [[Emily Hampshire]]\n* [[Barbara Sukowa]]}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 4\n| num_episodes             = 47\n| list_episodes            = List of 12 Monkeys episodes\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Trevor Rabin]]\n* Paul Linford\n* [[Bryce Jacobs]]\n* [[Stephen Barton]]}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Jake Kurily (seasons 1\u20132)\n* Rebecca Kirsch (season 1)\n* [[Richard E. Robbins]] (season 2)\n* Tony Elliott (season 3\u20134)\n* Sean Tretta (season 3\u20134)}}\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Richard Suckle]]\n* [[Charles Roven]]\n* [[Natalie Chaidez]] (season 1)\n* [[Jeffrey Reiner]]  (pilot)\n* [[David Grossman (director)|David Grossman]] {{nowrap|(season 2\u20134)}}\n* Travis Fickett (season 2)\n* Terry Matalas {{nowrap|(season 2\u20134)}}}}\n| location                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada\n* [[Detroit, Michigan]], US (pilot)\n* [[Republic of Macedonia]] (season 1)\n* [[Dominican Republic]] (season 1)\n* [[Budapest, Hungary]] (season 2)\n* [[Prague, Czech Republic]] (season 3\u20134)\n}}\n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Todd McMullen]] (pilot)\n* David Greene\n* Tico Poulakakis\n* Boris Mojsovski}}\n| editor                   = \n| camera                   = [[Single-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 40\u201348 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* Division Street (season 3\u20134)\n* [[Atlas Entertainment]]\n* [[Universal Content Productions|Universal Cable Productions]]\n}}\n| distributor              = [[NBCUniversal Television Distribution]]\n| network                  = [[Syfy]]\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[5.1]] ([[Surround]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundandpicture.com/2015/02/postapocalyptic-sound-syfys-12-monkeys/|title=The 'Post'apocalyptic Sound of Syfy's 12 Monkeys - Sound & Picture|date=February 6, 2015|website=soundandpicture.com|accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref>\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2015|1|16}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2018|7|6}}\n| website                  = http://www.syfy.com/12monkeys\n| website_title            = Official website\n}}\n\n'''''12 Monkeys''''' is an American [[television series]] on [[Syfy]] created by [[Terry Matalas]] and Travis Fickett. It is a [[science fiction]] [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] with a [[Time travel in fiction|time traveling plot]] loosely adapting the 1995 [[12 Monkeys|film of the same name]], which was written by [[David Peoples|David]] and [[Janet Peoples]] and directed by [[Terry Gilliam]], itself being inspired by [[Chris Marker]]'s 1962 [[featurette]] ''[[La Jet\u00e9e]]''; the series credits Marker and both Peoples for their original works.\n\nIn the series, [[Aaron Stanford]] and [[Amanda Schull]] star as James Cole and Dr. Cassandra \"Cassie\" Railly, two strangers destiny brought together on a mission to use [[time travel]] to stop the destructive plans of the enigmatic organization \"Army of the 12 Monkeys\". [[Kirk Acevedo]] and [[Noah Bean]] also star in the first season. In the second season, Bean makes a guest appearance, and [[Todd Stashwick]], [[Emily Hampshire]], and [[Barbara Sukowa]] are promoted from recurring guests to regulars. In the fourth season, Acevedo moves from starring to recurring guest star. Stanford, Schull, and Hampshire play reimagined versions of characters respectively portrayed by [[Bruce Willis]], [[Madeleine Stowe]], and [[Brad Pitt]] in the 1995 film. Stowe made a guest appearance in the second season in a small but pivotal role.\n\n[[Natalie Chaidez]] was the [[showrunner]] of ''12 Monkeys'' during its first season, working closely with creators Matalas and Fickett. For the second season, she stepped down to the role of consultant and Matalas and Fickett became showrunners. In the third and fourth seasons Fickett became a consultant, and Matalas was the sole showrunner. The series was produced by [[Atlas Entertainment]], which also made the 1995 film, and [[Universal Content Productions|Universal Cable Productions]]. [[Charles Roven]], producer of the original film, was one of the series [[executive producers]].\n\n''12 Monkeys'' premiered on January 16, 2015, with a 13-episode first season which received mixed to positive critical reception, and ended with the completion of its 11-episode fourth season on July 6, 2018, for a total of 47 episodes produced. From its second season and onward, it enjoyed more consistently favorable critical reception. The series won two awards for its [[cinematography]], one by each of the [[American Society of Cinematographers|American]] and [[Canadian Society of Cinematographers|Canadian Societies of Cinematographers]], and was nominated for a further four.\n\n==Plot==\n{{further|List of 12 Monkeys episodes}}\nIn the year 2043, [[Waste picker|scavenger]] James Cole ([[Aaron Stanford]]) has been recruited by a team of \"Project Splinter\" scientists led by physicist Katarina Jones ([[Barbara Sukowa]]), to [[Time travel|travel back in time]] to the year 2015, and stop the release of a deadly virus by the enigmatic organization known as the \"Army of the 12 Monkeys\". In Cole's original timeline, the virus caused a [[Pandemic|plague]] (Kalavirus) that resulted in the death of seven billion humans in the year 2017, and its on-going mutations will mean the eventual end of the human race. In the 2015 timeline, Cole will meet and enlist the help of brilliant [[virologist]] Dr. Cassandra \"Cassie\" Railly ([[Amanda Schull]]); the two are brought together because a recording mentioning Cole, that Cassie made after the viral outbreak, is uncovered by Katarina Jones in the future timeline, prompting her to select Cole for the mission. Cole will also encounter a seemingly unstable math genius named Jennifer Goines ([[Emily Hampshire]]), whose father Cole has been tasked to kill, Cassie's ex-boyfriend Aaron Marker ([[Noah Bean]]), and the dangerous high-ranking members of the Army of the 12 Monkeys, \"Pallid Man\" ([[Tom Noonan]]) and Olivia ([[Alisen Down]]). In the future timeline, Cole will also have to deal with his best friend Jos\u00e9 Ramse ([[Kirk Acevedo]]), and a man named Theodore Deacon ([[Todd Stashwick]]), who leads a brutal pack of scavengers from which Cole and Ramse fled. Meanwhile, Cole and Cassie will try to unveil the identity and whereabouts of the mysterious leader of the Army of the 12 Monkeys, who is only known as \"The Witness\" and who is always one step ahead of them.\n{{:List of 12 Monkeys episodes}}\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n* [[Aaron Stanford]] as James Cole, a scavenger who travels back in time to stop the plague and redeem himself from his troubled past<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/12-monkeys-everything-need-know-season-two/ |title=12 Monkeys: everything you need to know for Season 2 |first=Ed |last=Gross |work=empireonline.com |accessdate=January 28, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Amanda Schull]] as Cassandra \"Cassie\" Railly, a virologist who leaves a message about the origins of the plague that scientists recover in the future<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* [[Kirk Acevedo]] as Jos\u00e9 Ramse (seasons 1\u20133; recurring season 4), Cole's best friend<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* [[Noah Bean]] as Aaron Marker (season 1; guest season 2), Cassie's ex-boyfriend and political insider<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* [[Todd Stashwick]] as Theodore Deacon (season 2\u20134; recurring season 1), leader of a brutal group of survivors called the West VII<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"comic con\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/10/comic-con-2015-12-monkeys-michael-hogan |title=Comic Con 2015: ''12 Monkeys'' lands ''Battlestar Galactica'' vet in season 2 |work=EW |first=Natalie |last=Abrams |accessdate=August 3, 2015 |date=July 11, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Emily Hampshire]] as Jennifer Goines (season 2\u20134; recurring season 1), daughter of Leland Goines and a math genius, who meets Cole in a psych ward<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2015/03/13/12-monkeys-emily-hampshire-series-regular-syfy/ |title=TVLine Items: Syfy's Newest Monkey, Diddy Does black-ish and More |date=March 13, 2015 |accessdate=April 22, 2015 |work=TVLine |first=Rebecca |last=Iannucci}}</ref>\n* [[Barbara Sukowa]] as Katarina Jones (n\u00e9e Werner) (season 2\u20134; recurring season 1), the inventor and operator of the time machine<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"comic con\"/>\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Tom Noonan]] as the man commonly referred as \"Tall Man\" by the characters,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2016/06/14/12-monkeys-hyena-review |title=12 Monkeys: \"Hyena\" Review |first=Christine |last=Seghers |date=June 13, 2016 |work=ign.com |accessdate=January 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/12monkeys/episodes/season/4/episode/5/after|title=After|website=syfy.com|accessdate=July 3, 2018}}</ref> and \"Pallid Man\" by the writers,<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/04/11/12-monkeys-executive-producer-on-season-1s-finale-and-what-to-expect-in-season-2 |title=12 Monkeys Executive Producer on Season 1's Finale and What to Expect in Season 2 |first=Eric |last=Goldman |date=April 11, 2015 |work=ign.com |accessdate=January 29, 2017}}</ref> who is the villainous face of the Army of the 12 Monkeys<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* [[Romina D'Ugo]] as Max (season 1; co-star season 4), a scavenger from the West VII group, and former lover of Cole<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2014/08/avan-jogia-to-topline-spike-tvs-tut-event-series-romina-dugo-joins-syfys-12-monkeys-814707/ |title=Avan Jogia To Topline Spike TV's 'Tut' Event Series; Romina D'Ugo Joins Syfy's '12 Monkeys' |author=The Deadline Team |date=August 5, 2014 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=January 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"TvLine\" />\n* [[Demore Barnes]] as Marcus Whitley, one of the few remaining soldiers of the U.S. military.<ref name=\"TvLine\">{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2014/08/06/syfy-12-monkeys-cast-lyriq-bent-todd-stashwick/ |title=Syfy's 12 Monkeys Adds Rookie Blue Vet, Originals Alum and Two Others |work=TVLine}}</ref>\n* Ramon de Ocampo as Oliver Peters (seasons 1\u20132), Markridge Group's medical researcher\n* [[Alisen Down]] as Olivia Kirschner, also known as \"Striking Woman\" outside the show, a high-ranking member of the Army of the 12 Monkeys<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* [[Amy Sloan]] as Elena (season 1), mother of Ramse's son\n* Andrew Gillies as Julian Adler (seasons 2\u20134; co-star season 1), a Project Splinter scientist\n* [[Michael Hogan (Canadian actor)|Michael Hogan]] as David Eckland (season 2), a charismatic and intelligent scientist from the future who had been Jones' partner in another reality.<ref name=\"comic con\"/>\n* [[Scottie Thompson]] as the unnamed woman referred by the writers as \"Mantis\" (season 2\u20134)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/12-monkeys-season-2-884643 |title='12 Monkeys' Season 2: Can the Time Travelers Actually Challenge Fate? |work=hollywoodreporter.com |accessdate=February 1, 2017}}</ref> a calculating and menacing time traveler, and mother of the Tall Man and Olivia<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/08/tanc-sade-cast-roadies-scottie-thompson-12-monkeys-1201490982/ |title=Tanc Sade Joins Showtime Pilot 'Roadies'; Scottie Thompson In Syfy's '12 Monkeys' |work=Deadline Hollywood |first=Denise |last=Petski |accessdate=August 3, 2015 |date=August 3, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Jay Karnes]] as Robert Gale (season 2\u20134), a savvy 1940s FBI agent who believes a series of grisly murders may have something to do with Cole, whom he suspects might not be from this time<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/08/10/12-monkeys-season-2-jay-karnes-brendan-coyle |title=12 Monkeys lands Downton Abbey, The Shield alums for season 2 |work=Entertainment Weekly |first=Natalie |last=Abrams |accessdate=August 10, 2015 |date=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Brooke Williams]] as Hannah Jones, also known as \"Zeit\" (season 2\u20134),  Katarina and Elliot Jones' biological daughter and the primary motivator for Jones to invent time travel to undo her death.\n* Murray Furrow as Dr. Lasky (seasons 3\u20134; co-star seasons 1\u20132), a Project Splinter scientist\n* [[Hannah Waddingham]] as Magdalena (season 3), a member of the Army of the 12 Monkeys charged with protecting The Witness and who has been dubbed \"both ruthless and expedient\" in her methods<ref name=\"S3Recurring\">{{cite web |url=http://nerdist.com/12-monkeys-game-of-thrones-star-trek-hannah-waddingham-faran-tahir-exclusive/ |title=12 MONKEYS CASTS GAME OF THRONES AND STAR TREK ACTORS (EXCLUSIVE) |work=Nerdist |first=Alicia |last=Lutes |date=December 14, 2016 |access-date=December 14, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161215150407/http://nerdist.com/12-monkeys-game-of-thrones-star-trek-hannah-waddingham-faran-tahir-exclusive/ |archive-date=December 15, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Faran Tahir]] as Mallick (season 3\u20134), an imposing and devout enforcer of the Army of the 12 Monkeys who resides in Titan<ref name=\"S3Recurring\"/>\n* [[James Callis]] as Athan Cole (season 3; co-star season 4), Cole and Railly's son, who has been raised by the Army of the 12 Monkeys to become their leader known as The Witness<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/12/08/12-monkeys-james-callis-season-3 |title=12 Monkeys adds Battlestar Galactica star in season 3 \u2013 exclusive |work=Entertainment Weekly |first=Natalie |last=Abrams |date=December 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/12-monkeys/265068/8-secrets-about-12-monkeys-season-3-every-fan-should-know |title=8 Secrets About 12 Monkeys Season 3 Every Fan Should Know |website=denofgeek.com |accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Julian Richings]] as an advisor to Olivia (season 4)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.postapocalypticmedia.com/12-monkeys-season-4-recap-review-first-three-episodes/ |title=12 Monkeys Season 4 Recap & Review: Diving Into the First 3 Enticing Episodes |date=June 15, 2018 |website=postapocalypticmedia.com |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Abigail Hardingham]] as Emma (season 4), also known as Marion Woods, Olivia's daughter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvgoodness.com/2018/06/28/12-monkeys-final-season-night-three-preview/|title=12 Monkeys Final Season Night Three Preview - TV Goodness}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n===Conception===\nTerry Matalas and Travis Fickett, who had written together for the series ''[[Nikita (TV series)|Nikita]]'' and ''[[Terra Nova (TV series)|Terra Nova]]'', wrote an original [[spec script]] [[television pilot]] with a [[Time travel in fiction|time travelling plot]], named ''Splinter''.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/12-monkeys-natalie-chaidez-interview/|title=12 MONKEYS: Natalie Chaidez Talks about What It Takes to Be a Successful Showrunner|date=April 3, 2015|work=collider.com|accessdate=January 23, 2017}}</ref> Eventually, the script found its way to [[Atlas Entertainment]]'s offices, who had produced the ''[[12 Monkeys]]'' movie and had been wanting to create a TV series based on it for some time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvgoodness.com/2015/04/10/aaron-stanford-travis-fickett-and-terry-matalas-talk-12-monkeys-exclusive/|title=Aaron Stanford, Travis Fickett, and Terry Matalas Talk 12 Monkeys [Exclusive]|first1=j! says: April|last1=13|first2=2015 at 5:04|last2=Am|date=April 11, 2015|work=tvgoodness.com|accessdate=January 23, 2017}}</ref> After some deliberation, Matalas and Fickett came to an agreement with Atlas Entertainment to transform ''Splinter'' into a ''12 Monkeys'' adaptation.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://io9.gizmodo.com/what-the-12-monkeys-showrunner-learned-from-writing-for-1679744051|title=What The 12 Monkeys Showrunner Learned From Writing For Terminator: SCC|first=Charlie Jane|last=Anders|work=gizmodo.com|accessdate=January 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvfanatic.com/2015/02/12-monkeys-creator-teases-the-red-forest-talks-causality-loops-a/|title=12 Monkeys Creator Teases The Red Forest, Talks Causality Loops & More|first=Henry A.|last=Otero|date=February 20, 2015|work=tvfanatic.com|accessdate=January 23, 2017}}</ref> According to Matalas, aside of the overall structure of the plot being an attempt to stop a man from doing something in the past, the concept of the same watch from different points in time, the terminology used for traveling through time (\"splintering\"), and the female lead character named \"Cassie\", most of the ''Splinter'' pilot was changed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/merrillbarr/2015/10/09/12-monkeys-season-2-nycc-terry-matalas/3/#4fba79885355|title=NYCC Exclusive: '12 Monkeys' Executive Producer Terry Matalas On Season 2 And Show's Roots|first=Merrill|last=Barr|work=forbes.com|accessdate=January 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Development===\n{{Quote box\n|width=35%\n|quote=\"Ultimately, our version of [[predestination]] \u2013 and where it diverges from ''[[La Jet\u00e9e]]'' or [[12 Monkeys|the original film]] \u2013 is that it's a basically a bullfight, a ballet, against [[Time]]. That Time is something to be wrestled with and fought against \u2013 and after you've bled and been beaten and gotten your ass thoroughly kicked, ''maybe'' you've moved it an inch.\n\nThe idea of a [[Causal loop|closed loop]] works beautifully in a film, but for the story and the emotion of a TV series to ''really'' resonate, the characters and the audience have to believe that [[Time travel in fiction#Changing the past|change]] is possible. It's hard-fought and not without [[Causality|causalities]] along the way, but we've already seen that time ''can'' be affected. Whether it can be changed ''enough'' \u2013 or how Time might account for those changes \u2013 are some of the central questions of the show. It's also possible that all of this is a closed loop with several loops inside that loop.\"\n|source=\u2014Terry Matalas, co-creator, on how the [[Time travel in fiction|time travel model]] of the series differs from that of its source material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.signaltonoisemag.com/allarticles/2016/6/30/the-power-of-a-paradox-a-lesson-about-time-travel-on-syfys-12-monkeys-part-i|title=The Power of a Paradox: A Lesson About Time Travel from SyFy's 12 Monkeys (Part I)|work=signaltonoisemag.com|accessdate=January 28, 2017}}</ref>\n|align=right\n}}\n\nOn July 22, 2013, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' first revealed that [[Syfy]] was developing a ''12 Monkeys'' television adaptation, in the form of a 90-minute [[Television pilot#Backdoor pilot|backdoor pilot]] that would lead to a straight-to-series order, similarly to what the [[Battlestar Galactica (miniseries)|''Battlestar Galactica'' miniseries]] did. The pitch for the pilot, which would be written by Matalas and Picket, was submitted to Syfy by Atlas Entertainment's [[Charles Roven]] and [[Richard Suckle]]; Roven was one of the producers of the original film. [[Jon Cassar]] was reported as being on board to direct.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/12-monkeys-adaptation-series-order-590140|title='12 Monkeys' Adaptation Near Series Order at Syfy (Exclusive)|work=hollywoodreporter.com|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> The following month, it was reported that Syfy decided to [[green-light]] an hour-long pilot, which would be executive produced by Roven and Suckle, with production set to begin in November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/12-monkeys-adaptation-gets-pilot-614489|title='12 Monkeys' Adaptation Gets Pilot Order at Syfy|work=hollywoodreporter.com|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Due to the series being labeled as \"cast contingent\", production could not move forward until the roles of Cole and Goines were cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2013/08/26/syfy-orders-12-monkeys-pilot/|title=SyFy orders '12 Monkeys' pilot|date=August 26, 2013|work=ew.com|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> On April 4, 2014, Syfy green-lit the first season, consisting of 13 episodes, including the pilot filmed in 2013. The pilot was directed and executive produced by [[Jeffrey Reiner]]; Matalas and Ficket, who wrote it, were announced to co-executive produce the season, while Natalie Chaidez would serve as [[showrunner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/1/syfy-greenlights-12-episodes-of-12-monkeys/251263/|title=Syfy Greenlights 12 Episodes of '12 Monkeys' (Updated)|date=April 4, 2014|work=zap2it.com|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Chaidez credited her experience writing for the first season of ''[[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]]'' and the two seasons of ''[[Terminator: The Sarah Connor Chronicles]]'', two science fiction series with time traveling plots, as valuable to understanding how to make ''12 Monkeys'' work.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Matalas presented the series as a \"complete [[Reboot (fiction)|reimagining]]\" of the film and not just a [[remake]], citing ''[[Looper (film)|Looper]]'' as an inspiration for the time travel visual effects.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/12-monkeys-producer-syfy-series-718532|title='12 Monkeys' Producer on Syfy Series: 'It's a Complete Reimagining'|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Philiana|last=Ng|date=July 14, 2014|accessdate=November 2, 2014}}</ref> In fact, as Matalas explained, the story of the film was adapted into the first [[Act (drama)|act]] of the pilot, and from there on, the series follows an original storyline, although it continues to homage both the film and ''[[La Jet\u00e9e]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/01/15/12-monkeys-tv-show-syfy-showcase_n_6480078.html|title='12 Monkeys' TV Show: Worth The Watch?|work=huffingtonpost.ca|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> [[Madeleine Stowe]], who played the equivalent of Amanda Schull's character in the film, narrated the opening of the season 2 premiere and made an appearance in its finale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2016/02/25/12-monkeys-madeleine-stowe-season-2-syfy/|title='12 Monkeys' taps Madeleine Stowe for special season 2 role \u2014 exclusive|date=February 25, 2016|work=ew.com|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> Two major differences compared to the movie are that this version of time travel allows for changes in the past to affect the future, and that the \"Army of the 12 Monkeys\" is a real organization rather than a [[red herring]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nerdist.com/exclusive-producers-travis-fickett-and-terry-matalas-on-time-travel-gender-swapping-and-syfys-12-monkeys/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Producers Travis Fickett and Terry Matalas on Time Travel, Gender Swapping, and Syfy's 12 MONKEYS - Nerdist|date=January 17, 2015|work=nerdist.com|accessdate=January 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202014835/http://nerdist.com/exclusive-producers-travis-fickett-and-terry-matalas-on-time-travel-gender-swapping-and-syfys-12-monkeys/|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe series creators plotted three seasons in advance, although they noted that the show could go on for longer than that.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/12-monkeys-tv-show-terry-matalas-travis-fickett-interview/|title=12 MONKEYS Interview: Creators Terry Matalas & Travis Fickett and Showrunner Natalie Chaidez|date=January 23, 2015|work=collider.com|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> During the second season they said they need four seasons to tell the complete story.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/article/16107-12-monkeys-showrunner-terry-matalas-talks-season-3-fate-and-ratings|title='12 Monkeys' Showrunner Terry Matalas Talks Season 3, Fate, and Ratings|work=inverse.com|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> The ending of the series has been known to them since the beginning. Matalas said about it: \"We have a definitive target in place. It's very emotional and it's going to make everyone cry.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hngn.com/articles/138473/20151009/12-monkeys-spoilers-cole-to-die-in-series-finale.htm|title='12 Monkeys' SPOILERS: Cole to Die in Series Finale?|first=Headlines & Global|last=News|date=October 9, 2015|work=hngn.com|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref> Chaidez said the ending is designed to \"circle back\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/12-monkeys-ending-pilot/|title=Syfy's 12 Monkeys Ending Will Circle Back to the Pilot|date=January 17, 2016|work=slashfilm.com|accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe series premiered on January 16, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movieweb.com/12-monkeys-tv-show-premiere/|title=12 Monkeys TV Show Will Premiere This January on Syfy|date=October 10, 2014|work=movieweb.com|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> and was renewed for a second season on March 12, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2015/03/12/12-monkeys-renewed-season-2-syfy/|title=12 Monkeys Renewed for Season 2|first1=Kimberly|last1=Roots|first2=Kimberly|last2=Roots|date=March 12, 2015|work=tvline.com|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> which premiered on April 18, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spoilertv.com/2016/01/12-monkeys-season-2-premiere-date.html|title=12 Monkeys - Season 2 - Premiere Date Announced + First Look Promotional Photos *Updated*|last=Assassin|work=spoilertv.com|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Matalas and Fickett, who had opted for Chaidez to showrun the first season because of her bigger experience working on TV, replaced her during the second season, after her departure to showrun her own TV series, ''[[Hunters (2016 TV series)|Hunters]]''.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Chaidez instead was credited as a consultant for the season.<ref name=\"auto\"/> The third season was announced on June 29, 2016,<ref name=\"ew.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/06/29/12-monkeys-season-3-renewal|title='12 Monkeys' renewed for season 3 \u2014 exclusive|date=June 29, 2016|work=ew.com|accessdate=January 28, 2017}}</ref> and premiered on May 19, 2017,<ref name=\"ew.com1\"/> with the first episode being the directorial debut for Matalas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/10/12-monkeys-christopher-lloyd-guest-star-season-3-syfy-series-1201839119/|title='12 Monkeys': Christopher Lloyd To Guest Star In Season 3 Of Syfy Series|first1=Denise|last1=Petski|first2=Denise|last2=Petski|date=October 19, 2016|work=deadline.com|accessdate=January 28, 2017}}</ref> Fickett left his position as executive producer and was credited as consultant, leaving Matalas the sole showrunner for the season. Nevertheless, Fickett provided the story and helped write the screenplay for the season's fourth episode, \"Brothers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spoilertv.com/2017/05/12-monkeys-mother-guardians-enemies.html|title=12 Monkeys - Mother & Guardians & Enemies & Brothers - Advance Preview - \"Four Episodes for the Price of One!\"|first=Lisa|last=Macklem|website=spoilertv.com|accessdate=May 20, 2017}}</ref> In a change over how the previous seasons were released, Syfy aired the entire third season over three consecutive nights. A fourth and final season was announced on March 16, 2017. It consisted of 11 episodes, which premiered on June 15, 2018, and concluded on July 6, 2018.<ref name=\"ew.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2017/03/16/12-monkeys-season-3-premiere-date-renewal/|title='12 Monkeys' Renewed for Fourth and Final Season|date=March 16, 2017|work=ew.com|accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/12-monkeys-will-go-back-to-the-middle-ages-for-season-4|title=12 Monkeys will go back to the Middle Ages for Season 4|last=Weiss|first=Josh|date=January 13, 2018|work=Syfy|accessdate=January 14, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/news/a856614/12-monkeys-final-season-air-date/|title=12 Monkeys' final season lands an air date |last=Mitchell|first=Bea|date=May 8, 2018|work=Syfy|accessdate=May 9, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Filming locations===\nThe pilot for ''12 Monkeys'' was filmed in [[Detroit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20131210/NEWS/131219981/sci-fi-pilot-12-monkeys-filming-in-detroit-will-get-1-5m-in-state|title=Sci-fi pilot '12 Monkeys' filming in Detroit, will get $1.5M in state incentives|date=December 10, 2013|work=crainsdetroit.com|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.assignmentx.com/2015/12-monkeys-producersshow-runners-exclusive-interview/|title=12 MONKEYS showrunners give the scoop on Season 1 - exclusive interview|website=assignmentx.com|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref> Starting with the second episode, the bulk of [[principal photography]] for the series took place in [[Toronto]], both [[Location shooting|on location]] and at the Cinespace Film Studios,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theobserver.ca/2015/11/25/syfy-show-12-monkeys-filming-at-imperial-oil-site|title=U.S. television show shooting in Sarnia|last=nurun.com|website=Sarnia Observer|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://playbackonline.ca/2014/07/30/syfys-12-monkeys-to-shoot-in-toronto/|title=Syfy's 12 Monkeys to shoot in Toronto|website=playbackonline.ca|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://playbackonline.ca/2016/06/30/toronto-shot-12-monkeys-renewed-for-season-three/|title=Toronto-shot 12 Monkeys renewed for season three|website=playbackonline.ca|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref> where they constructed sets like the room with the time machine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goldenekamera.de/Best_of_Entertainment/article207653361/Hinter-den-Kulissen-von-12-Monkeys-2-0.html|title=Hinter den Kulissen von \"12 Monkeys\" 2.0|first=Anke|last=Hofmann|website=goldenekamera.de|accessdate=July 4, 2018 |language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/touring-toronto-on-location-with-syfys-12-109913709825.html|title=Touring Toronto: On Location With Syfy's '12 Monkeys'|website=yahoo.com|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAdditional filming for the first season took place in the [[Republic of Macedonia]], standing in for [[Chechnya]], and the [[Dominican Republic]], masquerading as [[Haiti]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/touring-toronto-on-location-with-syfys-12-109913709825.html|title=Touring Toronto: On Location With Syfy's '12 Monkeys'|website=yahoo.com|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://macedoniaonline.eu/content/view/27072/|title=MINA Breaking News - US TV Series films Three Episodes in Macedonia|website=macedoniaonline.eu|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> During the second season, production filmed for roughly 10 days in [[Budapest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nerdist.com/12-monkeys-cast-teases-season-2-surprises/|title=12 MONKEYS Cast Teases Season 2 Surprises - Nerdist|date=October 20, 2015|work=nerdist.com|accessdate=January 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202040110/http://nerdist.com/12-monkeys-cast-teases-season-2-surprises/|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=matalas_interview_2016-06-14>{{cite web|url=https://www.assignmentx.com/2016/12-monkeys-terry-matalas-exclusive-interview/|title=12 MONKEYS: Terry Matalas talks Season 2 - exclusive interview|work=assignmentx.com|date=June 14, 2016|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Filming in [[Prague]] took place for about three weeks for the third season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2017/05/17/12-monkeys-cast-and-ep-talk-season-3s-new-eras-and-new-binge-ready-schedule|title=12 Monkeys Cast and EP Talk Season 3's New Eras and New Binge-Ready Schedule|first=Eric|last=Goldman|date=May 17, 2017|website=ign.com|accessdate=May 20, 2017}}</ref> The reason for moving to Europe was to benefit from the different flair and to use the older architecture for 1950s stand-ins.<ref name=matalas_interview_2016-06-14 /> Production returned to Prague for the fourth season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetvjunkies.com/12-monkeys-terry-matalas-talks-season-4-part-1/|title=12 Monkeys: Terry Matalas Talks Season 4, Part 1|first1=Henry A|last1=Otero|date=June 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvgoodness.com/2018/06/15/amanda-schull-talks-12-monkeys-season-4-premiere-night-exclusive/|title=Amanda Schull Talks 12 Monkeys Season 4 Premiere Night [Exclusive] - TV Goodness|first=Heather|last=M}}</ref> Standing sets used in the series were changed constantly to reflect both older and newer versions of the locales and also alterations to the locations that resulted from the characters' trips through time.<ref name=matalas_interview_2016-06-14 />\n\n===Cinematography===\n[[Todd McMullen]] served as director of photography for the pilot, but once the series was ordered to series, David Greene replaced him. After shooting the first five episodes, Greene asked the producers if it would be possible to bring in an additional cinematographer so that they could alternate. Tico Poulakakis was brought in and filmed three episodes for the first season. In the second season, Greene and Poulakakis were joined by Boris Mojsovski, who became Greene's main alternate until the end of the series. To get more shooting days out of the production's schedule, two camera units shot in parallel resulting in episodes featuring work done by both Greene and Mojsovski.<ref>http://www.csc.ca/publications/2018/201805/IssueWeb201805.pdf</ref> Mojsovski said about his close collaboration with Greene: \"David and I were constantly working in unison. I'd prelight his sets and he'd prelight mine; I'd shoot one-third of his episode, and he'd shoot one-third of mine. We got so good at that, today we don't know who shot what!\"<ref name=\"ascmag.com\">{{cite web|url=https://ascmag.com/articles/12-monkeys-time-independent|title=12 Monkeys: Time Independent - The American Society of Cinematographers|website=ascmag.com|accessdate=July 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nStylistically, for the scenes set in the bleak future timeline, the production team decided to use a palette of constant blue and green tones, as well as smoke and atmosphere, to differentiate it from the ones set in the present timeline. The present timeline often used a wider range of colors. Green decided to ignore the visual style of the original film, as he felt the series told a different story than it had.<ref name=\"creativeplanetnetwork.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.creativeplanetnetwork.com/news/12-monkeys-time-travels-2015-science-fiction-tale-reimagined-syfy-series-607895|title='12 Monkeys' Time Travels to 2015: The Science Fiction Tale Is Reimagined as a Syfy Series|website=creativeplanetnetwork.com|accessdate=July 3, 2018}}</ref> Instead, Greene's biggest stylistic influence while establishing the show's look in the first season was the film ''[[Children of Men]]'', which he referenced for the look of the future timeline.<ref name=\"ascmag.com\"/>\n\nFilming for the show was done [[Digital cinematography|digitally]] in [[1080p]]. For the first season, the cinematographers used the [[Arri Alexa]] Classic EV camera. Beginning with the second season, they transitioned to using the Alexa Mini. Lenses used for the first two seasons were [[Cooke Optics|Cooke]] 5/i and S4, and [[Leica Camera|Leica]] Summilux-C later. Green mentioned using [[Panavision]] Primo lenses as well. In the third season, the [[Freefly Systems|MoVi]] [[camera stabilizer]] was used, and for a scene where Cole encounters his future self, the [[Motion control photography|motion control]] Technodolly.<ref name=\"ascmag.com\"/><ref name=\"creativeplanetnetwork.com\"/><ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web|url=https://theasc.com/ac_magazine/December2015/ASCTVSeriesNominees/page3.html|title=The ASC -- American Cinematographer: ASC TV Series Nominees:|website=theasc.com|accessdate=July 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Society of Cinematographers]] has recognized the artistry and craftsmanship behind the show's cinematography by awarding it once and nominating it another two times, in categories relating to \"Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography\".<ref name=\"ascmag.com\"/> The [[Canadian Society of Cinematographers]] similarly recognized it with one award and one nomination in the category of \"TV Series Cinematography\".<ref name=\"csc.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.csc.ca/CSCawards/2016/|title=CSC Awards 2016|website=csc.ca|accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"csc.ca1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.csc.ca/CSCawards/2017/|title=CSC Awards 2017|website=csc.ca|accessdate=July 31, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170409112739/http://www.csc.ca/CSCawards/2017/|archive-date=April 9, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Visual effects===\nFor the first season of ''12 Monkeys'', [[visual effects]] for the series were provided by [[Stargate Studios]]. Typical effects work included the \"splintering\" time travel effect, [[matte paintings]] of the decayed future timeline, and enhancing the stage sets.<ref name=\"creativeplanetnetwork.com\"/> Starting with the second season, Folks VFX took over. According to Sebastien Bergeron, founder and VFX [[supervisor]] at Folks VFX, an episode of ''12 Monkeys'' has 60\u201375 effects shots on average, but any given episode could have as low as 30 or as high as 100\u2013125 shots. Bergeron said the bulk of their work was creating \"unseen environments\", but other instances of their output included \"environment work, big futuristic cities, a time-traveling city, twinning of characters when they meet themselves in the past, destruction, explosions, all sorts of FX and particles \u2013 pretty much everything. There are also situations when we freeze the time, and then one character walks in the shot.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://area.autodesk.com/life-in-3d/folks-vfx-offers-12-facts-about-syfy-series-12-monkeys/|title=Folks VFX offers 12 facts about \"12 Monkeys\" \u2013 Life in 3D \u2013 AREA by Autodesk|website=Area by Autodesk|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n[[Trevor Rabin]] and his longtime assistant Paul Linford composed the series' music for its first two seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/music/features/trevor-rabin-billion-dollar-composer-1201526098/ |title=Trevor Rabin's Rousing Scores a Testament to Life After Yes |first=Jon |last=Burlingame |date=June 23, 2015 |work=variety.com |accessdate=February 1, 2017}}</ref> [[Var\u00e8se Sarabande]] released the composers' score for the first season, consisting of 23 tracks, digitally and on CD, on July 31, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/12-Monkeys-Original-Television-Linford/dp/B00YZ6MY1S/ |title=12 Monkeys: Music From Syfy Original Television Series |date=July 31, 2015 |accessdate=February 1, 2017 |via=Amazon}}</ref> Rabin called it \"a hybrid score of [[Folk instrument|ethnic sounds]], [[orchestra]], and [[Electronic music|electronic]], with a strong theme base\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://top40-charts.com/news.php?nid=112053 |title=Varese Sarabande Records To Release 12 Monkeys - Original Television Soundtrack |work=top40-charts.com |accessdate=February 1, 2017}}</ref> The original film's theme music \u2013 an arrangement of [[Astor Piazzolla]]'s ''[[Suite Punta del Este]]'' made by [[Paul Buckmaster]] \u2013 can be heard during the ninth episode of the second season, \"Hyena\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvfanatic.com/2016/06/12-monkeys-season-2-episode-9-review-hyena/ |title=12 Monkeys Season 2 Episode 9 Review: Hyena |first=Henry A. |last=Otero |date=June 13, 2016 |work=tvfanatic.com |accessdate=February 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nRabin and Linford did not return for the remaining seasons of the show. Instead, the music for the first few episodes of the third season was composed by [[Bryce Jacobs]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2016/12/02/bryce-jacobs-to-score-12-monkeys-season-3/ |title=Bryce Jacobs to Score '12 Monkeys' Season 3 - Film Music Reporter |first=Matt |last=says |work=filmmusicreporter.com |accessdate=February 1, 2017}}</ref> [[Stephen Barton]] composed additional music for those episodes and took over as composer for the remaining episodes of the season, and the next.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/TerryMatalas/status/841141530979065856 |title=Terry Matalas on Twitter |website=twitter.com |accessdate=May 20, 2017}}</ref> Barton's score for season 3 was released by Var\u00e8se Sarabande on December 15, 2017, on CD \u2013 and later digitally \u2013 and consists of 27 tracks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2017/11/04/12-monkeys-season-3-soundtrack-announced/ |title='12 Monkeys' Season 3 Soundtrack Announced -  Film Music Reporter |website=filmmusicreporter.com |accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/12-Monkeys-Season-Three-Original/dp/B076DGTVML |title=12 Monkeys Season Three: Music From The Syfy Original Series |date=December 15, 2017 |accessdate=July 2, 2018 |via=Amazon}}</ref>\n\nThe fourth season's score was released digitally on June 15, 2018, by [[Lakeshore Records]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/12-monkeys/274196/12-monkeys-season-4-exclusive-track-foreshadows-epic-ending |title=12 Monkeys Season 4: Exclusive Track Foreshadows Epic Ending |website=denofgeek.com |accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> It consists of 31 tracks by Barton.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Monkeys-Original-Soundtrack-Stephen-Barton/dp/B07DMB9K1L/ |title=12 Monkeys |accessdate=July 2, 2018 |via=Amazon}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Broadcast===\n[[Syfy (UK and Ireland)|Syfy UK]] acquired regional broadcasting rights and ''12 Monkeys'' premiered in the UK on February 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tvwise.co.uk/2014/12/syfy-sets-uk-premiere-date-12-monkeys/|title=Syfy Sets UK Premiere Date For '12 Monkeys'|publisher=TVWise|date=December 29, 2014|accessdate=January 1, 2015}}</ref> The second season premiered April 27, 2016,<ref name=\"auto2\"/> and the third season May 26, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvwise.co.uk/2017/04/syfy-sets-uk-premiere-date-12-monkeys-season-3/|title=Syfy Sets UK Premiere Date For '12 Monkeys ' Season 3|date=April 1, 2017|website=tvwise.co.uk|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref> Syfy UK chose not to acquire the fourth and final season of the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvwise.co.uk/2018/10/syfy-uk-drops-12-monkeys-after-three-seasons/|title=SYFY UK Drops '12 Monkeys' After Three Seasons|date=October 3, 2018|website=tvwise.co.uk|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n[[Universal Pictures Home Entertainment]] released all four seasons on [[DVD-Video|DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/from-universal-pictures-home-entertainment-12-monkeys-season-one-300177097.html|title=From Universal Pictures Home Entertainment: 12 Monkeys: Season One|first=Universal Pictures Home|last=Entertainment|work=prnewswire.com|accessdate=January 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/12-Monkeys-Season-2/22765|title=12 Monkeys DVD news: Announcement for Season 2 - TVShowsOnDVD.com|work=tvshowsondvd.com|accessdate=January 28, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202061915/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/12-Monkeys-Season-2/22765|archivedate=February 2, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=23526|title=Universal: 12 Monkeys Seasons Three and Four Coming to Blu-ray in August|publisher=|accessdate=May 20, 2019|via=www.blu-ray.com}}</ref> In Australia, Via Vision Entertainment released on DVD and Blu-ray the third season on May 23, 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=23317|title=12 Monkeys: Season Three Blu-ray|website=blu-ray.com|accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref> and the fourth on January 2, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://viavision.com.au/shop/12-monkeys-season-four/|title=12 Monkeys Season Four|website=Via Vision Entertainment|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://viavision.com.au/shop/12-monkeys-season-four-blu-ray/|title=12 Monkeys Season Four Blu-ray|website=Via Vision Entertainment|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref> Both Australian sets lack subtitles, while the third season's set also lacks any extras.\n\nAll four seasons are available for digital purchase on Amazon [[Prime Video]] and [[iTunes]].<ref>https://www.amazon.com/gp/video/detail/B00R1NHRTQ/</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/tv-season/12-monkeys-series-1-3/id1254297775|title=12 Monkeys, Series 1 - 3|publisher=|accessdate=May 20, 2019|via=itunes.apple.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/tv-season/12-monkeys-season-4/id1386329498|title=12 Monkeys, Season 4|publisher=|accessdate=May 20, 2019|via=itunes.apple.com}}</ref>\n\nSyfy and [[Hulu]] announced that Hulu would exclusively make the first season available for streaming on February 24, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hulu.com/press/hulu-acquires-exclusive-streaming-rights-to-syfys-12-monkeys-in-new-deal-with-nbcuniversal/|title=Hulu Acquires Exclusive Streaming Rights to Syfy's 12 MONKEYS in New Deal with NBCUniversal \u2013 Hulu Press Site|website=hulu.com|accessdate=May 20, 2017}}</ref> Hulu added the second season on April 18, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/netflix-amazon-hulu-shows-and-films-coming-and-going-april-572248|title=All of the shows and films coming to Netflix, Amazon and Hulu in April|first=Stav Ziv On 3/23/17 at 9:30 AM|last=EDT|date=March 23, 2017|website=Newsweek|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref> the third on May 16, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/04/16/hulu-may-new-shows-movies/|title=What\u2019s on Hulu in May: Best shows and movies to watch this month|website=EW.com|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref> and the fourth season on June 15, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/whats-coming-to-hulu-june-2019/|title=What's Coming to Hulu in June 2019 - TV Guide|date=May 15, 2019|website=TVGuide.com|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref> Hulu's exclusivity agreement only covers the US; outside its borders, [[Netflix]] has made the first three seasons of the show available in multiple regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whats-on-netflix.com/news/is-seasons-1-to-4-of-12-monkeys-on-netflix/|title=Is Seasons 1 to 4 of '12 Monkeys' on Netflix?|date=June 29, 2018|website=What's on Netflix|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe complete DVD and Blu-ray sets will be released by [[Mill Creek Entertainment]] on July 14, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/tvshowsondvd/posts/10157972098216063?__tn__=K-R|author=TVShowsonDVD|title=***** TV SHOWS ON DVD ROUNDUP ***** MODERN FAMILY! 12 MONKEYS! BLOOD! SPONGEBOB SQUAREPANTS!|date=April 10, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|website=Facebook}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\nCritical reaction to the first season of ''12 Monkeys'' was mixed to positive. [[Rotten Tomatoes]], a [[review aggregator]] website, reported a 60% critical approval rating with an average rating of 5.98/10 based on 42 reviews. The website's critical consensus reads, \"The nonsensical time travel in ''12 Monkeys'' makes it less watchable than its original source material, but the high quality execution and cool characters are top-notch.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/12_monkeys/s01|title=12 Monkeys: Season 1|publisher=|accessdate=May 20, 2019|via=www.rottentomatoes.com}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which uses a [[weighted average]], the season was assigned a score of 57 out of 100, based on 25 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/12-monkeys-2015/season-1|title=12 Monkeys (2015)|publisher=|accessdate=May 20, 2019|via=www.metacritic.com}}</ref> Christine Seghers rated the first season 8.8/10 and wrote in her review for [[IGN]]: \"What started as a simple 'let's go back and fix this' story soon blossomed into a deep philosophical mediation on the concept of predestination versus free will. If you ''wanted'' it. The show is also an awful lot of fun.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/04/25/12-monkeys-season-1-review |title=12 Monkeys: Season 1 Review |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=June 20, 2016}}</ref> The critical reception of the later episodes of the first season was more positive than the initial reception. The final episode of the season, ''Arms of Mine'', received rave reviews, including a 9.4/10 rating from IGN and a 4.5/5 rating from [[Den of Geek]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/04/11/12-monkeys-arms-of-mine-review |title=12 Monkeys: \"Arms of Mine\" Review |last=Seghers |first=Christine |date=2015-04-10 |website=IGN |accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/12-monkeys/245358/12-monkeys-season-finale-review-arms-of-mine |title=12 Monkeys Season Finale Review: Arms of Mine |work=Den of Geek |accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref> The twelfth episode of the season, called ''Paradox'', also received rave reviews, including a 9.3/10 rating from IGN and a A- rating from [[The A.V. Club|The AV Club]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/04/04/12-monkeys-paradox-review |title=12 Monkeys: \"Paradox\" Review |last=Seghers |first=Christine |date=2015-04-03 |website=IGN |accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tv.avclub.com/c/tv-review/12-monkeys/season-1 |title=TV Reviews \u2013 12 Monkeys \u2013 Season 1 |website=TV Club |accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe second season was received positively. Rotten Tomatoes indexed 12 reviews and reported an 92% critical approval rating with an average rating of 8.07/10. The assigned critical consensus reads: \"Full of addictive twists, the second season of ''12 Monkeys'' overcomes time traveling logic issues with help of added thriller elements.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/12_monkeys/s02|title=12 Monkeys: Season 2|publisher=|accessdate=May 20, 2019|via=www.rottentomatoes.com}}</ref> Seghers, rating the season 9.0/10, wrote for IGN: \"In its outstanding sophomore season, 12 Monkeys became bigger, bolder and more beautifully baffling, reaffirming its status as one of the best sci-fi shows on television today.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2016/08/04/12-monkeys-season-2-review |title=12 Monkeys: Season 2 Review |first=Christine |last=Seghers |date=August 4, 2016 |work=ign.com |accessdate=January 28, 2017}}</ref> The episodes ''Lullaby'' and ''Memory of Tomorrow'' are generally considered to be the best episodes of the second season. ''Lullaby'' has a 9.4/10 rating from IGN and a perfect 5/5 rating from Den of Geek.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2016/06/07/12-monkeys-lullaby-review |title=12 Monkeys: \"Lullaby\" Review |last=Seghers |first=Christine |date=2016-06-06 |website=IGN  |accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/12-monkeys/255996/12-monkeys-lullaby-review |title=12 Monkeys: Lullaby Review |work=Den of Geek |accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref> ''Memory of Tomorrow'' has a 9.6/10 rating from IGN and a 4.5/5 rating from Den of Geek.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2016/07/19/12-monkeys-memory-of-tomorrow-review |title=12 Monkeys: \"Memory of Tomorrow\" Review |last=Seghers |first=Christine |date=2016-07-18 |website=IGN |accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/12-monkeys/257098/12-monkeys-season-2-finale-review |title=12 Monkeys Season 2 Finale Review |work=Den of Geek |accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor the third season of ''12 Monkeys'', Rotten Tomatoes indexed 10 positive reviews, leading to a 100% critical approval rating with an average rating of 9.1/10. The following critical consensus is assigned to the season: \"''12 Monkeys''' third season satiates fans' hunger for fresh thrills, startling twists, and titillating time travel.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/12_monkeys/s03|title=12 Monkeys: Season 3|publisher=|accessdate=May 20, 2019|via=www.rottentomatoes.com}}</ref>\n\nRotten Tomatoes indexed 11 positive reviews for the fourth season, producing a 100% critical approval rating with an average rating of 9.33/10. The critical consensus of the website reads: \"''12 Monkeys'' continues to raise the bar with each marvelously complex episode in a knock-out fourth season that proves as unpredictable as it is gratifying.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/12_monkeys/s04|title=12 Monkeys: Season 4|publisher=|accessdate=May 20, 2019|via=www.rottentomatoes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Creative response===\nBefore the ''12 Monkeys'' series premiere, [[Terry Gilliam]], director of the original film, expressed his reservations about the concept: \"It doesn't have anything to do with me and no-one has contacted me. It's a very dumb idea. ... If it was going to be any good it would have to be written by [[David Peoples|David]] and [[Janet Peoples]], who wrote the film, otherwise it would just be another version of ''[[Time Bandits]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scifinow.co.uk/news/12-monkeys-tv-show-a-very-dumb-idea-says-terry-gilliam/|title=12 Monkeys TV show \"A very dumb idea\" says Terry Gilliam|work=scifinow.co.uk|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> In another interview, Gilliam sounded apprehensive regarding whether [[Chris Marker]] \u2013 the author of ''[[La Jet\u00e9e]]'', the [[featurette]] that inspired Gilliam's film \u2013 would approve of the series: \"I think that they've got just another time travel series. Of course, Chris Marker is dead, so he doesn't have to see it, what ''La Jet\u00e9e'' spawned.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/the-zero-theorem/239025/terry-gilliam-talks-the-zero-theorem-television-and-radiohead|title=Terry Gilliam Talks The Zero Theorem, Television, And Radiohead|website=denofgeek.com|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> However, according to Matalas, both the Peoples and Marker read the pilot and gave the series creators their blessing and support to move forward with it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailydead.com/exclusive-qa-12-monkeys-tv-series-showrunner-terry-matalas/|title=Exclusive Q&A with 12 Monkeys TV Series Co-Executive Producer Terry Matalas - Daily Dead|date=February 2, 2015|work=dailydead.com|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> The Peoples and Marker are credited in the opening and closing credits of each episode for their respective original works.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2015/04/10/entertainment-geekly-why-12-monkeys-works/|title=Entertainment Geekly: 'The City on the Edge of Forever and why '12 Monkeys' works|date=April 10, 2015|work=ew.com|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> [[Madeleine Stowe]], lead actress of the original film, became supportive of the filmmakers after watching the pilot, appreciating the differences between her character and Amanda Schull's interpretation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/12-moneys-season-2-terry-matalas-showrunner-interview/|title='12 Monkeys' Showrunner Terry Matalas on Season 2 and Cassie & Cole's Relationship|date=July 15, 2016|work=collider.com|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> She was later cast in a pivotal role in the second season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2016/02/25/12-monkeys-madeleine-stowe-season-2-syfy/|title='12 Monkeys' taps Madeleine Stowe for special season 2 role \u2014 exclusive|date=February 25, 2016|work=ew.com|accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Nominee !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2015 || [[Golden Maple Awards]] || [[Golden Maple Awards#Newcomer of the Year in a TV Series Broadcasted in the US|Newcomer of the Year in a TV Series Broadcast in the U.S.]] || [[Emily Hampshire]] || {{won}} || <ref>{{cite web|title=Brandon Jay McLaren, Amanda Crew Win Golden Maple Awards|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/brandon-jay-mclaren-amanda-crew-806436|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=April 8, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[42nd Saturn Awards|Saturn Awards]] || [[Saturn Award for Best Syndicated/Cable Television Series|Best Syndicated/Cable Television Series]] || ''12 Monkeys'' || {{nom}} || <ref>{{cite web|title=2015 Saturn Awards: 'Captain America: Winter Soldier,' 'Walking Dead' lead nominees|url=https://ew.com/article/2015/03/04/saturn-awards-captain-america-walking-dead/|website=EW.com|accessdate=April 8, 2017|date=March 4, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2015 American Society of Cinematographers Awards|American Society of Cinem